{[%evp 0,31,12,-16,17,19,32,7,16,9,13,11,33,24,6,3,5,11,41,42,49,53,42,53,77,
26,36,19,21,-45,-5,20,24,9]} 1. b3 a5 $5 {In blitz chess, particularly online,
the move 1...a5 is quite popular. Objectively speaking, by opting for 1.b3, we
are indeed giving Black greater freedom, meaning that even if Black responds
with 1...a5, it doesn’t necessarily lead to any terrible consequences for
him. What results is a position where the effectiveness of a5 versus b3 is in
question. Personally, I find the answer to which move is more advantageous
quite clear...} 2. Bb2 a4 {the logical follow-up} ({of course Black can play
some other moves, where a5 will just be useful, but a little bit less useful
than our b3} 2... d5 3. e3 {just a better version for us compared to 1.b3 d5
lines}) 3. b4 $1 e6 (3... e5 4. a3 d6 5. c4 {just a good version for White of
the English opening. Eventually, the a4 pawn could be weak after White plays Nc3
}) 4. a3 Nf6 5. e3 c5 {this is the logical follow-up of Black's play} (5... b6
6. c4 Bb7 7. Nf3 c5 8. bxc5 bxc5 (8... Bxc5 9. Nc3 $16 {some problems for the
a4 pawn}) 9. Nc3 Qa5 10. Rb1 $16) 6. bxc5 Bxc5 7. c4 d5 8. Nf3 dxc4 {Black's
best reaction} (8... O-O 9. Nc3 Qa5 (9... dxc4 10. Nxa4 $16) 10. cxd5 exd5 11.
Bd3 (11. Rb1 Bf5 $1 $11) 11... Nc6 12. Ne2 $14 {Ng3 next}) 9. Bxc4 O-O 10. Nc3
Bd7 11. O-O Be7 $1 (11... Qa5 {dubious in my opinion because Black needs to
leave the a5 square for Nc6-Na5 ideas} 12. Ne5 Be8 13. d4 Be7 14. Qe2 Nc6 15.
Nf3 $14) 12. Re1 {preparing e2-e4} (12. Ne5 Be8 13. d4 Nc6 14. Nf3 Na5 $1 $11)
(12. e4 b5 $1 13. Nxb5 Nxe4 $11) 12... Qa5 13. e4 Rc8 14. Ba2 Na6 15. e5 Ne8
16. Re3 $5 $36 {eventually Nd4-Rh3 with huge attacking chances for White} *

