{[%evp 0,35,20,-24,22,6,42,-5,10,10,2,10,17,20,17,-6,20,24,18,18,27,-12,19,19,
18,18,17,15,33,14,27,18,18,3,3,0,0,-17]} 1. b3 c5 2. Bb2 d6 {this is connected
with e7-e5 ideas later. Black is trying to build a strong barrier against our
Bb2. Of course will will try to break it. We will play g3-Bg2-c4-e3-Nge2-00
and f2-f4 or d2-d4 later} (2... d5 {[%emt 0:00:07] will be analyzed later, via
the move order 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 c5 in Chapter 6 and}) (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 (3. g3 $6 {
would be wrong because Black can play} d5 {[%emt 0:00:07] transposing into a
good version for him of Chapter 6 and}) 3... Nf6 (3... d5 4. e3 {[%emt 0:00:07]
trans in Chapter 6 and}) (3... d6 4. d4 $1 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 (5... Bd7 6. e4 Nf6
7. Nc3 $14) (5... Nf6 6. e3 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 Bd7 10. Nc3 $14 {
typically slightly better position. Black is solid but for sure he didn't
equalize}) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. g3 Nf6 8. Bg2 Qc7 9. c4 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O Be6
12. e4 $14 {White will double rooks on the 'd' line and will enjoy a slightly
better position}) 4. c4 {now Black has 3 possible ways to continue: g6-Bg7-00
in typical Symmetrical English style, d7-d5 immediately, or e7-e6 followed by
d7-d5. We should know how to play against each of Black's set-ups} (4. d4 $6 {
now would be wrong because Black can play d7-d5 in one move} cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5
$11) 4... d5 {the most concrete option} (4... g6 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d6
8. d4 {we have transposed into Chapter 12 of the First part of this repertoire!
}) (4... e6 5. g3 d5 {this is typical "Tarrasch style"} 6. cxd5 (6. Bg2 $6 {
would be a huge positional mistake} d4 $1 $17 {and Black is just better}) 6...
exd5 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 {we have transposed into a good line of the
Tarrasch defence. Of course, we cannot go too deep here, as the Tarrasch topic
would deserve a full database itself, but we'll mention the key ideas of the
position} Ne4 $1 {is the modern move, where Black tries to equalize in a
concrete way} (9... Bg4 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 Re8 12. Rc1 Bf8 13. h3 Bh5 14. e3
$14 {with the idea Ne2-Nf4}) (9... Be6 {is the classical approach to the
position, but here White is just slightly better:} 10. Nc3 Rc8 11. Rc1 $14) 10.
Nc3 $5 {is a more promising way in our opinion} (10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12.
Bxc3 d4 13. Bb2 Bf5 $11 {here Black doesn't have problems}) 10... Bf6 11. Na4
cxd4 $1 {the modern move, even if only the 4th most played move in practice} (
11... b5 $2 {looks that this move refutes 11.Na4, but here White has a key
tactical idea} 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Rc1 $1 $16) (11... b6 12. dxc5 Bxb2 13. Nxb2
bxc5 14. Na4 $14) (11... Re8 12. Rc1 b6 13. dxc5 Bxb2 14. Nxb2 bxc5 15. Na4 $14
) 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. Rc1 Qe7 $1 {against Nc5 ideas. Here it is not easy for
White to achieve an advantage according to the engine. You can play 14. Nxc6-Bxc6
15.Bd4 or 14.e3 immediately. In both cases, the engine evaluation just stays on
+0,15. But you shouldn't worry too much. The position remains playable and for
sure more pleasant to play from the White side.} (13... Re8 {allows} 14. Nc5 $1
Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bb5 16. Re1 $14)) 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 {Now Black has a few
different paths: 6...Nxc3 immediately, 6...e5 or 6...Nc7 in typical maroczy
style} e5 (6... Nc7 $6 {the problem for Black here is that White is very fast
to create some counterplay:} 7. Rc1 (7. e3 $5 {an other possible move order} e5
8. Rc1 {trans}) 7... e5 8. e3 $1 Be7 9. Ne4 Qd5 10. Ng3 O-O 11. Bc4 Qd6 12. O-O
$16) (6... Nxc3 7. Bxc3 f6 {of course Black wants to play with e7-e5, limiting
our dark squares bishop} 8. e3 e5 9. Bc4 Bf5 {[%emt 0:00:00] the best
according to engine. Black plays for} (9... Qd6 {was played against me in an
online blitz game} 10. O-O Be6 11. d4 $1 Bxc4 12. bxc4 cxd4 13. exd4 exd4 14.
Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Be7 16. Qh5+ g6 17. Qb5+ Qc6 {½-½ Jobava,B (2578)
-Babazada,K (2479) Titled Tuesday intern op 17th Jan Early Chess.com INT blitz
2023 (6)} 18. Qb3 $1 {would have been much stronger} O-O 19. c5+ Kg7 20. Rfe1
$14 {we can continue with Re6 and all our pieces are much more active}) 10. Qe2
$1 $146 {against Bd3} (10. O-O $6 Bd3 $1 $15) 10... Qe7 $1 (10... Qd7 11. d4 $1
$14 {and Black has problems because of the opposition Qe2-Ke8}) 11. O-O O-O-O
12. Nh4 Be6 13. f4 $13 {Black's precision has led us to a dynamic and fiercely
contested position. With opportunities abound for both sides, the engine
evaluates the position at a razor-thin 0.05. Personally, I sense White enjoys
superior coordination, yet the excitement lies in the uncertainty ahead.
Anything can happen from here.}) 7. e3 Nxc3 (7... Ndb4 $6 8. Qb1 $1 Be6 9. a3
Nd5 10. Bd3 $14) 8. dxc3 $1 (8. Bxc3 $6 Bd6 $13 {Comparing this position to
the 6...Nxc3 7.Bxc3 variation, Black hasn't spent a move on f7-f6.
Consequently, not only does Black possess an additional tempo, but the c4-g8
diagonal is not weak anymore. These factors contribute to my hesitation in
entering this 8.Bxc3 line, which has been chosen by the majority of the players}
) 8... Bf5 {has been played in the game Keymer-Gelfand. Even if it was a blitz
game we need to pay some attention} (8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 {we are happy in this
endgame. Now we want to play Bc4-Bd5} f6 (9... Be6 $6 {trying to prevent our
idea leads only to worse consequences for Black} 10. Ng5 Bf5 11. Bc4 Bg6 12.
Bd5 $14) 10. Bc4 $14) (8... Qf6 9. Bd3 Bf5 10. e4 O-O-O 11. Qe2 $14) 9. Nd2 $1
{White wants to play e3-e4} e4 $1 {critical} (9... Be7 10. e4 Be6 11. Bc4 $14)
10. Qc2 Qe7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. Bb5 Qe6 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. f3 {Keymer-Gelfand.
Both players have demonstrated remarkable prowess to arrive at this point.
Essentially, White will gain the e4 pawn, albeit at the expense of
compromising his pawn structure. In return, Black will have good
compensation for the sacrificed pawn. True, should anyone arrive at this point,
it will be hard to win with the White pieces. Thus far, only a maestro like
Gelfand was able to reach this position. It's important to mention that White
faces minimal risk in this position, as the burden lies on Black to prove the
adequacy of his compensation}) 3. g3 e5 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. c4 g6 {this is the most
logical development for Black} (5... f5 $6 {this is positionally dubious, and
has never been played at a high level. The move f7-f5 is trying to take some
extra space, but in reality, it just creates weaknesses} 6. e3 Nf6 7. Ne2 Be7 8.
O-O O-O 9. Nbc3 Be6 10. d4 $14 ({the typical} 10. f4 $14 {is also possible.
Just that in this case d4 is even stronger. But as a rule, you should know that
whenever Black plays with f7-f5, we can play f2-f4 and we are at least slightly
better})) 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e3 Nge7 8. Nge2 O-O (8... h5 {has been tried sometimes.
We just play} 9. h3 Be6 (9... h4 $6 10. g4 $14) 10. Ne4 $1 {immediately
exploiting the weakness of the g5 square} h4 11. g4 f5 12. Ng5 Bd7 13. gxf5
gxf5 (13... Nxf5 $6 14. Rg1 $16) 14. Rg1 $14) 9. O-O {In this position Black
has two main ideas: play for b7-b5 or play for d6-d5} Be6 {now we should be
careful as White because if Black manages to play d6-d5 he can be even
slightly better} (9... a6 10. d3 Rb8 {trans in 9...Rb8}) (9... Rb8 {Black
wants to play a fast b7-b5. The problem for him is that this costs some time}
10. d3 a6 11. Qd2 b5 12. f4 $1 {the right plan} f5 13. Nd5 Bb7 (13... Be6 {
we will see a model game Pantsulaia-Yakovenko in the model games section}) 14.
Rae1 Nxd5 $6 15. cxd5 Nb4 {has been played in the rapid game Carlsen-Saric,
now White had to play} 16. Nc3 $1 {defending both the d5 and the a2 pawn. Next,
we want to play a3 and it's not clear at all how to play with Black}) 10. Nd5
$1 (10. d3 $6 d5 $1 $15) 10... Qd7 {Black wants to play Bh3} (10... f5 $6 {
we are happy to see this move} 11. d3 Qd7 12. f4 $1 $14) 11. Nec3 Bh3 (11... f5
12. f4 $14 {typical}) 12. Bxh3 Qxh3 13. f4 $1 {the position is complicated,
but I like White:} Qd7 14. f5 $5 {very interesting move that I wanted to
mention} (14. fxe5 {also possible} Nxd5 15. Nxd5 dxe5 16. e4 {where the
evaluation is between equal and slightly better for White}) 14... Nxf5 (14...
gxf5 $6 15. Qh5 $40 {White will continue with Rf1-Raf1 with huge initiative on
the kingside}) 15. Ne4 Kh8 16. g4 Nh6 (16... Nfe7 17. Ndf6 $14) 17. g5 Ng8 18.
Bc3 $1 $44 {an important move: we are stopping Nb4, next we want to continue
with Qf3-Rf2-Raf1 and we have a huge compensation for the pawn} (18. Qe2 Nb4 $1
$11) *

