{[%evp 0,31,20,-26,-16,-16,3,1,4,4,2,-4,25,-6,17,3,-6,-35,-34,-12,-12,-22,-21,
1,8,8,0,6,6,6,6,6,6,22]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 {In this Chapter we will deal with
the move 2...Bg4, but we'll also speak about move orders. After 2...Nf6 should
White starts with 3.e3 or 3.Nf3? We'll try to give you an answer or at least a
way to build for yourself an answer} Bg4 {When facing these "Slav" lines,
referring to variations where Black looks to develop with Bf5 or Bg4 (which
could arise also with the move order 2...c6 followed by Bf5 or Bg4), White
must act decisively to counter Black's customary setups. More detailed
strategies on this topic will be explored in Chapter 5. Concerning the Bg4
lines specifically, the game can here "explode" very fast. As White, it is
very important to know the concrete move orderds} (2... Nf6 {Now the question
arises: how should we commence? If there's a suspicion that our opponent might
opt for Bf5, it's wiser to initiate with Nf3. This choice aligns with our
forthcoming strategy outlined in Chapter 4, where we intend to follow up with
g3, Bg2, and 0-0. Conversely, if there's a likelihood of Black playing Bg4,
then initiating with 3.e3 becomes a viable consideration. Generally speaking,
it's challenging to definitively declare whether 3.e3 or 3.Nf3 is superior.
Therefore, let's observe the outcome if Black adopts a course of action
contrary to our intended strategy} 3. Nf3 (3. e3 Bf5 {our opponent somehow
tricked us, but don't worry, if your feeling was wrong you can still play a
game knowing that nothing terrible happened!} 4. Nf3 e6 5. c4 c6 6. Nc3 h6 (
6... Nbd7 7. Nh4 Bg4 (7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. g3 $14) 8. Be2 Bxe2 9. Nxe2 $5
Bd6 10. f4 O-O 11. Nf3 {With an equal and playable position}) 7. d4 Nbd7 8. Bd3
Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {we reached just a playable position in which White has the more
pleasant side} Bb4 {is considered more precise} (9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. e4
dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 (13... Re8 14. Rfe1 Qc7 15. Rad1 $14) 14. Qe2
$14) 10. O-O O-O {now because of Bb4 it will be harder for White to execute
e3-e4 as Black can play Bxc3-Bxc3-Nxe4} 11. a3 Ba5 (11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Ne4 13.
Bb2 a5 14. a4 $14 {Black is solid but White has for sure the more pleasant
side. +0,30 according to engine}) 12. Nd2 $5 (12. b4 Bc7 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4
Nxe4 15. Qxe4 a5 {this is probably Black's best and the position is very close
to complete equality}) 12... Qe7 13. Rad1 Rad8 14. Rfe1 Rfe8 15. e4 {again
Black should have some ways to equalize but from the practical point of view
White has the more pleasant side}) 3... Bg4 4. e3 Nbd7 (4... e6 $5 5. h3 Bh5 6.
d3 (6. g4 $6 {we will play this move in the same position with Black having
played Nbd7 instead of e6. But now it's a mistake!} Bg6 7. g5 {Black has now}
Nfd7 $1 $15 {with a very comfortable position for him. Of course, Nfd7 wouldn't
be possible if Black would have played Nbd7 instead of e6!}) 6... Nbd7 (6...
Be7 7. g4 $1 {now it's possible because the g7 pawn will be hanging at the end
of the line:} Bg6 8. Ne5 Nbd7 9. Nxd7 Nxd7 (9... Qxd7 10. g5 $1 $18) 10. Bxg7
$16) (6... h6 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 Bh7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Nd2 Be7 12. f4
$14) 7. g4 Bg6 8. Nh4 Bd6 (8... Bb4+ $5 9. Nd2 O-O (9... Ne4 $2 10. Nxg6 Nxd2 (
10... Bxd2+ 11. Ke2 hxg6 12. dxe4 Bb4 13. Bg2 $16) 11. Nxh8 Nc4+ 12. c3 Nxb2
13. Qc2 $16) 10. g5 Bh5 11. Be2 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Ne8 13. f4 $14 {000 next}) 9. g5
$1 Nh5 10. Rg1 {we simply want to play Be2 so Black has to do something about
it} Be7 11. Qg4 $36 {not easy to continue with Black} (11. Be2 $2 Bxg5 $1 {
attacking Nh4})) 5. h3 Bxf3 (5... Bh5 {transposes into the main line of this
chapter}) 6. Qxf3 e6 (6... e5 $6 {this is inaccurate from a conceptual point
of view: White has the light squares bishop, so it's better for Black to put
the pawns on the light squares, so 6...e6 would have been much better} 7. g4 $1
c6 8. c4 $36) 7. c4 c6 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. g3 O-O 10. Bg2 $14 {/= Black is very
solid but we can play a long game thanks to our bishops pair}) 3. Nf3 (3. f3 {
is very popular, but strategically and objectively dubious, so we'll suggest
going for something more sound}) 3... Nd7 (3... Bxf3 {is something that
shouldn't worry us too much. White obtains a pleasant and playable position
with the bishops pair} 4. exf3 e6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 (6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 8.
f4 O-O 9. d4 $1 $14 {this is important as we don't want to give our opponent
the possibility to deprive us of the bishop's pair. We will continue with
Nd2-Nf3 and we have a playable slightly better position} (9. d3 c5 10. Nd2 Ne8
$1 {and Black is absolutely fine})) 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 c5 9. d3 Nc6 10. c4 Qc7
11. Nc3 $14) 4. e3 Ngf6 (4... e5 5. h3 Bxf3 (5... Bh5 $2 {not possible now} 6.
g4 Bg6 7. Nxe5 $16) 6. Qxf3 Ngf6 7. g4 $14) 5. h3 Bh5 6. g4 Bg6 7. g5 $1 Ne4 (
7... Ng8 $5 {interesting and has been played by Weasley So} 8. h4 Bh5 $1 9. Be2
h6 {Artemiev-So 2021} 10. Nh2 $5 $146 {is a move I like a lot, because now the
most precise move for Black would be the counterintuitive Bg6!} Bg6 $1 (10...
Bxe2 11. Qxe2 hxg5 12. hxg5 e5 13. Qg4 $14 {Nc3-000 next}) 11. Bh5 $1 Bxh5 12.
Qxh5 e6 13. Qg4 Ne7 14. f4 Nf5 15. Nf3 $14 {we'll continue with Nc3-000 with a
very interesting position}) 8. h4 $5 {can be a very very interesting
alternative} (8. d3 {is the more "positional" option} Nd6 9. Nbd2 e6 (9... h6
10. Nh4 $1 Bh7 11. gxh6 e5 12. Rg1 $3 {somebody could say that this is not
very positional!} Qxh4 13. hxg7 Bxg7 14. Rxg7 $13) 10. Rg1 $132 {we can
continue with Nh4-Qg4-000}) 8... h6 $1 {critical, and was played in the game
Zherebuk-Shirov World Cup 2021} (8... h5 $2 9. d3 Nd6 10. Nbd2 $16 {Qe2-Bh3
next}) (8... Bh5 9. d3 Nd6 10. Be2 h6 (10... e6 11. Nfd2 $1 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 h6
13. Rg1 $14 {then Nc3-000}) 11. Rg1 e6 12. Nfd2 Bg6 (12... Bxe2 {trans in 10...
e6}) 13. Bh5 $36) 9. h5 $5 $146 hxg5 10. hxg6 Rxh1 11. gxf7+ Kxf7 12. d3 Nxf2
$3 (12... Nef6 $2 13. Nxg5+ Kg8 14. Qf3 $40) 13. Qe2 $3 Nxd3+ $3 14. cxd3 e6
15. Qg2 Rh6 16. Nc3 {+0,20 according to the engine, I don't know what it means.
... :)} *

