{[%evp 0,33,20,-34,-18,-18,-18,-19,-14,-12,-23,-14,-11,-14,13,13,13,0,16,10,31,
22,21,12,21,14,54,35,42,20,27,31,34,34,27,22]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Bf5 {now that
our opponent committed to Bf5 we can continue accordingly to this information:}
3. Nf3 e6 (3... Nf6 4. g3 e6 5. Bg2 {trans}) 4. g3 $1 {against Bf5 we will go
for the double Fianchetto. In general Black can play Nf6 before e6, but this
doesn't change anything} Nf6 5. Bg2 {now Black needs to decide if to include
or not the move h7-h6. If he doesn't we might consider playing Nh4} h6 {
Black spends a tempo but now he doesn't need to deal with the complications
arising after 5...Be7 6.Nh4 that, I can assure you, not many players want to
face from the Black side} (5... Be7 6. Nh4 $5 Bg4 (6... Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Nxg6
hxg6 9. f4 c5 (9... O-O $6 {better for Black to wait a little bit before
castling} 10. e3 c5 11. g4 $5 Nc6 12. g5 Nh5 13. Bf3 $36) 10. e3 Nc6 11. Qe2
Qc7 12. Nc3 Rd8 {Both sides have played useful moves before castling} 13. O-O {
soon or later we have to do it. Still, from the practical point of view, you
will meet a lot of players that will rush with 00 from the Black side. In that
case, you can consider g3-g4 ideas} O-O 14. g4 $5 $36 {we can enjoy our
position thanks to the bishops pair}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Nfd7 $1 {critical} (8...
Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. e3 $14 {just a better version for White compared to the
6...Be4 line, as now he has already played for free the move g3-g4}) 9. Nf5 $1
$146 {I invite the readers to open a bottle of champagne!} exf5 10. gxh5 Bf6 (
10... Nf6 11. e3 (11. Nc3 $5 c6 12. e3 {Ne2-Nd4 next with a very interesting
game}) 11... c6 12. c4 O-O 13. Qf3 Qd7 14. Nc3 Rd8 15. O-O-O $14) 11. d4 $1 {
of course, we don't want to let Black deprive us of the bishops pair} c6 12.
Qd3 g6 13. c4 $36) 6. O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2 {we have reached the key
position of this chapter. Now Black can play immediately c6, or start with Bh7,
or with a5, that are usually anyway transposing into a Slav set-up} c6 (8... c5
{Black wants to play with Nc6} 9. Ne5 $1 {preventing Nc6} Nbd7 (9... Nc6 $6 10.
Nxc6 bxc6 11. e4 Bh7 12. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6]}) 10. e4 Bh7 11. Re1 Nxe5 12.
Bxe5 Nd7 13. Bb2 Bf6 14. e5 Be7 15. c4 $14) (8... a5 9. a3 Bh7 10. Re1 Nbd7 11.
e4 c6 {trans}) (8... Bh7 9. Re1 a5 10. a3 c6 11. e4 {trans}) (8... Nbd7 9. Re1
c6 10. e4 Bh7 {trans}) 9. Re1 a5 {the inclusion of a5-a3 is useful for Black,
so it makes sense to check the line via this move order} 10. a3 Bh7 11. e4 {
and now Black should decide how to develop his Nb8. He has 3 options: Nbd7,
Na6 or c6-c5 followed by Nc6} Nbd7 {the classical move, and the best in my
opinion} (11... c5 $6 {ambitious but Black is not in time} 12. exd5 $1 exd5 (
12... Nxd5 13. Ne5 Nd7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. a4 Ra6 16. Nc4 $16 {
Kuzubov-Gustafsson 2011}) 13. Ne5 Nc6 14. Ndc4 $3 $146 dxc4 $2 (14... Rc8 15.
Nxc6 Rxc6 16. Nxa5 $16) (14... Re8 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Ne5 Qb6 17. Rb1 $5 $14 {
defending our Bb2}) 15. Bxc6 $16) (11... Na6 12. Ne5 $1 {taking profit of the
fact that Black didn't develop with Nbd7} Nc5 (12... Nd7 $2 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14.
Qg4 Bg6 15. h4 h5 16. Qe2 $16 {Bf3 next against the h5 pawn}) 13. exd5 $1 exd5
(13... cxd5 14. d4 Ncd7 (14... Nce4 15. c4 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Be4 17. c5 $14) 15. c4
Rc8 16. Qe2 $14) 14. Ndf3 Ncd7 15. Qd2 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 $14 {Re2-Rae1 next}) 12.
Qe2 Qb6 {Black wants to play a5-a4, and when White will answer with b3-b4
Black might have c6-c5 ideas} (12... b5 {very human decision: Black tries to
play something fast on the queenside} 13. a4 $1 Qb6 (13... b4 $6 {this is a
big positional mistake. Black should create some counterplay on the queenside.
If he closes the position with b4, not White has a free hand on the kingside} 14.
Kh1 $1 {the start of a very nice plan} Rc8 15. Ng1 $1 {exactly! White's idea
is to play Ng1 and f2-f4} Qc7 16. e5 Ne8 17. f4 $16) 14. Bd4 $5 {asking Black
some questions} Bc5 (14... c5 15. Bb2 $14 {now Black doesn't have the c5
square for one of his pieces!}) 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 16. exd5 cxd5 (16... exd5 17. Qe3
$14) 17. axb5 Qxb5 18. Qe3 $132 {With a balaneced position. Black is solid but
his Bh7 is still out of the game}) 13. a4 $5 {preventing Black's ideas. It's
now more about ideas than concrete moves, for this reason, we will check two
high-level games: Vitiugov-Bluebaum and Caruana-Giri. We will try to understand
how it was possible to improve the play for both White and Black} Rfc8 (13...
Rfd8 14. exd5 $5 (14. e5 Ne8 15. Kh1 {Vitiugov uses the above-mentioned idea,
but here it doesn't work so well because the queenside is not closed now} Qa6
16. h4 b5 $1 17. Qe3 {½-½ Vitiugov, N (2712)-Bluebaum, M (2670) AUT-chT 2324
Austria 2023 (5.2)} Nc7 $1 $13 {Black wants to continue with c5-Nb6 with some
counterplay on the queenside}) 14... cxd5 15. Nd4 {White will continue with
Nb5 and has a pleasant position in my opinion}) 14. Rec1 $1 $146 {Ra1 can
still be useful in defending the queenside} (14. exd5 $6 {now this would be a
mistake because Rfc8 is much more useful then Rac8} cxd5 15. Nd4 Bc5 $1 16. Nb5
Bxf2+ $1 17. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 18. Kxf2 Rxc2 $15 {so we can conclude that 14.exd5
doesn't work now for concrete reasons}) (14. Rac1 {the idea is good, but
Caruana has chosen the wrong rook!} Bc5 (14... Bb4 $5 {also annoying against
Re1}) 15. e5 Ne8 16. Nf1 {0-1 Caruana,F (2792)-Giri,A (2772) Tata Steel-A 84th
Wijk aan Zee 2022 (6)} Qa6 $1 {Black wants to play with b7-b5 and it's clear
that White would have liked to have a rook on the 'a' line}) 14... Bc5 {
this is how the game Caruana-Giri continued, with the only difference of Ra1
instead of Re1} (14... Bb4 {doesn't make sense now as our rook is on a1 and
not on e1} 15. e5 Ne8 16. Nf1 $14) (14... Rd8 {engine shows a move like this,
but of course, if we would need to check all the possible moves in the position
it would require a week of work and a few databases! In fact nobody, even at
the highest level, is checking move per move a position like this: it's more
about the ideas!}) 15. e5 Ne8 16. Nf1 Qa6 17. g4 $1 $40 {now that we have a
rook on a1 Black's counterplay on the queenside will be much slower. For this
reason, we can immediately start developing some initiative on the kingside. We
will continue with h4-Ng3 with good attacking chances} *

