{[%evp 0,31,15,-20,-2,-7,11,2,3,7,0,2,9,9,9,9,18,9,9,8,9,9,8,7,7,7,3,4,21,5,5,
-2,0,-2]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c6 {in this chapter we will deal with the systems
where Black is playing in the Slav style, with d5+c6. Here it is very
important to be precise on the first moves, as we don't want to give Black the
possibility to build his dream set-up (Nf6-Bf5-h6-Bh7-e6-Nbd7-00, if Black can
play all these moves, he is usually fine)} 3. e3 {In general Black is choosing
between 2 approaches: systems with Bg4 or systems with Bf5. With our move
order, we are first dealing with the Bg4 approaches, and we are not giving
Black the opportunity to play them. In fact after 3.e3 Bg4 is not possible, so
if Black wants to play Bg4 he should play Nf6 now} Nf6 (3... Bf5 {Black can go
immediately for Bf5, but now we have an interesting possibility} 4. g4 $5 {
played only in 12 games, but a very challenging direction} Bg6 (4... Be4 $6 {
already this is not very precise} 5. Nf3 $1 e6 (5... Nf6 $2 6. g5 Nfd7 7. h4 e6
8. Nc3 Bf5 9. Nd4 $16 {and Black cannot preserve his light squares bishop}) (
5... Nd7 {Black delays Nf6, so that sometimes f7-f6 followed by Bg6-Bf7 is
possible} 6. d3 Bg6 7. h4 f6 8. h5 Bf7 9. Bh3 e5 10. g5 $1 Bd6 11. Nbd2 Qe7 (
11... Ne7 12. Qe2 $16 {already winning for White according to engine}) (11...
fxg5 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Nxe5 $14) 12. Nh4 $1 Be6 13. gxf6 gxf6 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15.
Bxf5 Nh6 16. Qf3 $14 {not terrible for Black, but for sure more pleasant for
White}) 6. d3 Bg6 {a logical human move, but strangely enough Black is not in
time:} (6... Bxf3 {this is the best according to engine, but it already shows
that White has won the first strategical battle in chasing Black's
light-squares bishop} 7. Qxf3 $14) 7. h4 h6 (7... h5 $6 8. Ne5 $16) 8. Ne5 Bh7
9. Nd2 f6 (9... Nf6 $6 10. g5 $1 $16) (9... Nd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Qe2 $1 {
[%emt 0:00:00] we are going for} O-O-O 12. O-O-O f6 {this limits the b2 bishop,
but now e6 is weak:} 13. e4 Bd6 14. g5 $1 hxg5 15. Bh3 $16) 10. Nef3 Bd6 11. g5
$1 Nd7 12. Rg1 hxg5 13. hxg5 $14 {already very unpleasant for Black}) 5. h4 h5
$1 {the most challenging continuation} (5... h6 6. d3 e6 7. Nd2 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7
9. f4 $14 {[%emt 0:00:00] we will simply continue with Qe2-Ngf3-Bh3 and}) 6. g5
Nd7 {very logical as Black wants to play with e7-e5, limiting Bb2, but here
comes a stunning novelty:} 7. Bh3 $1 $146 {our idea is to play f4-f5 very fast}
(7. d3 e5 $1 $15) 7... e6 {this is for sure logical against Bh3, but the
problem for Black now is that it will be hard for him to develop Bf8 as g7 is
always hanging} (7... e5 {Black hopes to play Bd6 next, now that Bb2 is not
attacking g7 anymore, but White is very fast in creating some counterplay} 8.
f4 $1 exf4 9. exf4 Ne7 10. Qe2 $16 {Black has already big problems. The best move
according to the engine is Bxc2 with the evaluation +1,00. This already shows that
something went wrong for him...}) 8. d3 Ne7 9. Nd2 Qc7 10. Ne2 $1 {we want to
play Ng3, taking control over the f5 square, or Nf4} O-O-O (10... Bf5 11. Ng3
Bxh3 12. Rxh3 $16) (10... e5 11. Ng3 O-O-O 12. Qe2 Kb8 13. O-O-O $16 {White's
plan is Rf1-f4}) 11. Nf4 Kb8 12. Qe2 {Black cannot move Bg6 as h5 will be
hanging, so we will take Nxg6 whenever we want} e5 13. Nxg6 Nxg6 14. O-O-O $14
{White has the bishops pair and a very pleasant position}) 4. Be2 {making sure
that Bg4 systems are not possible} Bf5 (4... h6 {sometimes Black plays this
kind of move, just to be sure that after Bf5-g4 he always had the h7 square.
On the other hand, this h6 move loses an important tempi} 5. c4 $1 {as a rule,
whenever Black is playing a slow move, we will play c4!} Bf5 6. Bxf6 $1 {
the critical direction. Now we need to analyze what happens in both pawn
structures exf6 or gxf6. Please take note of the fact that we are playing
Bxf6 ONLY because Black cannot take back with a piece, and because Black has
lost a tempo on the move h7-h6} exf6 (6... gxf6 7. Nf3 e6 8. O-O Bd6 9. d4 $1 {
White will simply go for the typical queenside game after c5-b4-a4-b5} Nd7 10.
c5 Bc7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. b4 a6 13. a4 $16 {White will continue with b5 and it is
not easy to suggest a good plan for Black. Also according to the engine here White
is just better}) 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. d4 $1 {again we want to play with c4-c5} O-O (
8... a5 {this could look logical, so that after c5-Bc7 it will not be so easy
for White to play b3-b4, but now we can go for some other ideas:} 9. O-O O-O
10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {Black needs to think about cxd5-cxd5-Nc3} Na6 12. Nc3 (
12. cxd5 $6 Nb4 $1 {Nxd5 will be possible}) 12... Nc7 13. c5 $1 {now that Bc7
is not possible, we will play c5} Be7 14. a3 $14 {b4 next. Black's position is
solid, but it should be quite pleasant to play from the White pieces. Just in
case the engine evaluates +0,40}) 9. c5 Bc7 10. b4 $1 ({after} 10. O-O {Black can
play with} a5 $1 {where we will need to spend some extra time in order to
create some play on the queenside}) 10... Nd7 11. Nc3 Re8 12. O-O {this is
actually not bad for Black. His position is very solid, and he can play in a
mix of Slav and Classical Caro-Kann (variation Nf6-Nxf6-exf6) style. He can
continue with Nf8-Ne6 and it's not so easy to break through with White. On
the other hand, we are the ones having a more pleasant position, for example:}
Nf8 (12... a6 13. a4 {the inclusion of a6-a4 usually goes into White's favour})
13. b5 Ne6 14. Nh4 $5 Bh7 15. Bd3 {fighting for the f5 square} Bxd3 16. Qxd3
Qd7 17. a4 Ba5 $1 18. Ne2 $14 {as I have already explained, Black is solid,
but it is pleasant to play from the White side}) 5. Nf3 (5. g4 {now we will
not go for this, as after} Bg6 6. h4 h6 {we have already committed with 
the move Be2, and as we have seen in the 3...Bf5 variation, sometimes our
bishop should go on h3}) 5... e6 (5... h6 6. Bxf6 $1 {after both recaptures
the game will transpose into 4...h6}) 6. Nh4 $1 {now we see why in many cases
Black is spending a tempo on the move h7-h6} Bg6 7. O-O {normally in this
position I would consider playing with 000, but the "problem" here is that we
have already played Be2, and now it will be harder to play with d3-Nd2 and Qe2,
exactly because the e2 square is already taken by our bishop!} Bd6 8. d3 Nbd7
9. Nd2 {In general we are not in a big hurry to take on g6, and we will try to
don't do it AT LEAST until Black hasn't played 00, otherwise after Nxg6-hxg6
the 'h' line could be a problem with the rook still on h8} O-O (9... Qe7 10. c4
e5 11. g3 {at some point Black should anyway play 00. If he will delay it even
further we have a lot of useful moves: Rc1-Qc2...}) 10. c4 {if you want you
can already play Nxg6, but I like to keep the tension for another few moves.
The position here is not forced, I will just try to present the "spirit" of
what can happen next} e5 {looks logical and tempting. And it is also good, so
why Black shouldn't play with e5?!} (10... Qe7 11. Rc1 Ba3 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13.
Qc2 a5 14. Bxa3 Qxa3 15. g3 {we shouldn't be worried about a4:} a4 16. b4 $1
Qxb4 17. Rb1 $14 {Rxb7 next}) 11. Rc1 Qe7 12. g3 Rfe8 (12... a5 13. cxd5 cxd5
14. e4 $5 dxe4 15. dxe4 $14 {Nxe4 is not possible because of Nxg6, while Bxe4
is not possible because of Nxe4-Nxe4-Nf5} Bxe4 $2 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Nf5 Qe6 18.
Nxd6 Nxd6 19. Ba3 $18) 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Nf3 Rac8 16. Kg2 {
I can tell you that it will not be easy to win here, but we are not risking
anything, and on the other hand Black will not have any way to force a draw,
so he has just to play a long game against our bishops pair, and maybe one day.
.. who knows how strong they will become :)} *

