{[%evp 0,35,25,-23,-23,-23,22,-5,8,0,-8,-10,-3,-6,11,24,24,29,16,11,11,15,24,
21,15,10,-12,-15,-3,2,9,3,22,34,21,11,12,16]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4.
Nf3 Nc6 {In this Chapter we will analyze the systems where Black plays with
d5+c5 and then Nc6 AND Nf6. In the next Chapter 7, we will analyze what happens
if Black plays only Nc6 OR Nf6} 5. Bb5 (5. c4 $2 {This is a huge positional
mistake when Nc6 is played, as now Black can continue with} d4 $1 $17) 5... Bd7
{The most popular move, and the best in my opinion} (5... Bg4 $6 {in general
this is a bad direction for Black} 6. h3 Bh5 (6... Bxf3 {this shouldn't even
be considered, we'll mention it just for the sake of completeness} 7. Qxf3 e6
8. c4 Be7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Nc3 $14 {0-0-Na4-Rc1 are the typical
moves that pose some problems on the c5 pawn}) 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 {this is just
bad for Black} Qc7 9. f4 e6 10. d3 Bd6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. h4 $16) (5... Qb6 6.
c4 $1 {now d5-d4 is not possible anymore} a6 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 {Black's queen will
not feel comfortable so exposed on the 'c' line:} 8. O-O e6 9. d4 dxc4 10. Nbd2
$1 {taking maximum profit of the better development} cxb3 11. axb3 b5 (11...
Be7 12. Ne5 Qc7 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Bd4 Qb5 15. Nec4 O-O 16. Ra5 $1 Qe8 17. Nb6
$16) 12. Ne5 Qb6 13. Qf3 $1 Bb7 14. Qg3 $36 {not easy at all to play with
Black. Also, the engine is not sure how to equalize here so White has at the very
least a strong initiative}) (5... a6 $6 {This is played when Black doesn't
believe in White's idea, but it's connected with a wrong assessment as after}
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Ne5 Qc7 8. O-O e6 9. f4 {White has a typical positional
advantage, for example:} Bd6 10. Rf3 $5 O-O 11. Rh3 $16) (5... e6 6. Bxc6+ $1 {
Compared to 5...a6, here Black hasn't spent a tempo, but on the other hand
he has already played e7-e6 which means that Bc8 cannot go out anymore from the
pawn chain} bxc6 7. d3 Bd6 8. e4 $1 {we need to be fast} (8. Nbd2 O-O 9. e4 e5
$1 $11) (8. O-O O-O 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 Nxe4 $11) 8... e5 $1 $146 {engine
shows this as the only way for Black to fight for the equality, and after:} (
8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Nxe4 10. Nbd2 $1 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 O-O 12. Qf3 Qc7 13. O-O-O $14
{White will continue with Ba3-Ne4-Bxc5 with a very nice positional edge}) (8...
Nd7 {a move that has been tried three times in practice} 9. Bxg7 Rg8 10. Bb2
Rxg2 11. e5 Be7 12. c4 Qc7 13. Nbd2 Bb7 14. Qe2 O-O-O 15. O-O-O $16 {
strategically much better for White}) 9. Bxe5 Bxe5 10. Nxe5 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12.
f4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Nxe4 15. Re1 Bf5 $1 16. g4 Bg6 17. Na3 f6 18.
Nxg6 hxg6 19. Re3 $14 {we reach an endgame where the engine will be able to hold,
but from a human point of view it is hard for Black because of the queenside
weaknesses}) (5... g6 $2 {was tried by some strong players, but it's a mistake!
} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Na4 $1 $146 {just refutes Black's set-up} Qa5 (7... Qd6 8. Be5
$1 $16) 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 $16 {Qe1 or c4 next}) 6. O-O a6 {
less played than 6...e6, but maybe even more critical from a strategical point
of view} (6... e6 7. c4 {we'll continue in this spyrit} a6 (7... Bd6 8. cxd5
exd5 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 $14 {/= the assessment of this position could go from
slightly better for White to equal, depending on personal taste.
Personally, I have always enjoyed playing against the isolated pawn when my
pieces are well developed}) (7... dxc4 8. bxc4 {this is solid for Black, but a
little bit sad, as for sure our position is more pleasant to play thanks to
our extra central pawn. Let's follow a game to understand better the typical
ideas} Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Rab1 Rad8 12. Rfd1 Bc8 13. h3 (13. Bxc6
$5 {could have been considered} Qxc6 14. Nb5 $14) 13... b6 14. a3 (14. d4 $1
cxd4 15. exd4 Na5 (15... Bb7 $2 16. d5 $1 $16) 16. Ne5 Bb7 17. Rbc1 $14) 14...
Bb7 15. Ba4 Na5 16. d3 Qb8 17. Ba1 Ne8 $1 {The strong GM Postny shows a great
understanding: Nf6 goes to f5!} 18. Nd2 Nd6 19. Nb5 Nf5 $1 {½-½ Sochacki,C 
(2487)-Postny,E (2562) FRA-chT Top 16 GpA Chartres 2022 (1.2) and Black was
fine in}) 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Ne5 Rc8 10. Nxc6 Rxc6 11. Bxf6 {trans in 6...a6}) (
6... g6 7. Nc3 $1 a6 (7... Bg7 $4 8. Nxd5 $18) 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. d4 cxd4 (9...
Bg7 10. dxc5 Ne4 11. Na4 Bxb2 12. Nxb2 O-O 13. b4 $14) 10. Nxd4 Bg7 11. Nxc6
bxc6 12. Na4 O-O 13. Rc1 $14 {Bd4-c4 next with a pleasant plus}) 7. Bxc6 Bxc6
8. Ne5 Rc8 (8... Qc7 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. c4 Rd8 11. Qf3 $14) 9. c4 e6 (9... dxc4
10. bxc4 e6 11. Nxc6 Rxc6 12. Bxf6 $5 {an interesting try, also a4 or Qb3 was
possible} Qxf6 13. Qb3 $1 Qe7 (13... Qxa1 $4 14. Qxb7 Rd6 15. Nc3 $18) 14. Nc3
$14 {for example, a typical human sequence could be} Qc7 15. Rab1 b6 16. Qa4
Qb7 17. d4 $18) 10. Nxc6 Rxc6 11. Bxf6 $5 {a very interesting try that has
been played already by some strong players} Qxf6 (11... gxf6 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13.
Nc3 Qd3 14. Rc1 Be7 15. Ne2 {1-0 Oparin,G (2654)-Eljanov,P (2691) ESP-chT
CECLUB Honor Toledo 2021 (5.2) we'll speak about this game in the model games
section}) 12. Nc3 d4 13. Ne4 $1 Qd8 (13... Qe5 14. Qc2 Be7 15. f4 Qc7 16. exd4
cxd4 17. d3 $14) 14. f4 Be7 15. Nf2 $5 {White wants to play e3-e4} dxe3 (15...
O-O $6 16. e4 $14) 16. dxe3 Qc7 (16... Qxd1 17. Raxd1 Rd6 18. g4 $14 {can be a
little bit unpleasant}) 17. Qe2 O-O 18. Rad1 {not much for White, Black is
very solid. The only good thing is that we have a slightly more pleasant
position, but to be honest not more than that. What to do, 1.b3 is not
refuting the game! :)} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7"]
[Black "d5+c5+Nf6 OR Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
