{[%evp 0,12,38,-10,-28,-28,19,5,-5,-5,8,-8,-15,0,-19]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 3. e3
{In the previous Chapter we have analyzed the lines where Black plays BOTH the
moves Nf6 and Nc6. Now we will deal with the lines where Black plays ONLY one
of them} Nf6 (3... a6 4. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes into 3...Nc6 4.Nf3 a6}) (3... Nc6
4. Nf3 a6 {very popoular: Black radically prevents Bb5 ideas, but at the cost
of one tempo} (4... e6 5. Bb5 Nge7 $5 (5... Bd7 6. O-O Nf6 7. c4 {[%emt 0:00:
06] transposes into the previous Chapter}) 6. c4 a6 7. Ba4 Bd7 8. O-O {has
been reached in 6 games} d4 (8... b5 $2 9. cxb5 Nb4 10. Nc3 Nd3 {
Naranyan-Alekseenko} 11. bxa6 $1 Nxb2 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qb1 Rxa6 14. Qxb2 $18)
(8... Rb8 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Ne5 Rc8 12. Qh5 Qc7 13. d3 g6 14. Qe2
f6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Nd2 $14) (8... Nf5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Ne5 $14)
9. Na3 $1 $146 {we want to play Nc2, immediately putting pressure on the d4
pawn} Nf5 10. Nc2 Be7 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Ne5 Rc8 (12... O-O 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. e4
$14) 13. exd4 cxd4 14. Re1 O-O 15. Qg4 Bc5 16. d3 {we will continue with
Re2-Rae1 and see what next. I like the position and the engine gives us a small
plus, 0,20 and I think it's enough to be optimistic about this line, where
Black had anyway to find many good moves in order to reach this position}) (
4... Bg4 {When Black plays c5+d5, in general, I don't think Bg4 set-ups should
worry us:} 5. Bb5 e6 6. h3 Bh5 (6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 $14) 7. g4 Bg6 8. h4 h5 9.
Ne5 Nge7 10. Nxg6 Nxg6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. gxh5 Nxh4 13. Qg4 Nf5 14. Nc3 $16) 5.
g3 {we will go now for the double Fianchetto. It's a special version as White
has included e3 and Black has included a6: we will count on the fact that the
move e3 will be more useful!} Qc7 {An ambitious move: PRO: It prepares e7-e5,
CONS: Black will not be able anymore to answer c2-c4 with d5-d4} (5... Nf6 6.
Bg2 Bf5 7. O-O e6 8. d4 {only now we will go for the Colle set-up. The reason
is that compared to the classical Colle lines, Black has spent a tempo on
the a7-a6 move, and a tempo on Bc8-Bf5, which is for sure well placed, but it
concretely can become a target:} Be7 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be7 11.
c4 $1 $14) 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nbd2 h6 {now Black has spent other 2 tempis: Be7,
and then Bxc5, and h7-h6} (10... O-O 11. Nh4 $1 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. c4 $14)
11. c4 O-O 12. a3 a5 {very logical, against b3-b4} 13. cxd5 exd5 (13... Nxd5 $4
14. e4 $1 $18 {again Bf5 becomes a target!}) 14. Rc1 Be7 (14... Ba7 15. Ne5 $14
) 15. Qe2 Qb6 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qa6 18. Qxa6 Rxa6 19. Bc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5 {
Black is very solid, but should be a bit more pleasant to play with White
against the IQP pawn. Still, don't forget that we cannot refute 1...d5! :)}) (
5... d4 $5 {interesting, but at least we haven't played the move c2-c4. This
means that sometimes we will be able to undermine Black's d4 pawn with the
move c2-c3, or use the c4 square for our Nb1} 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bg2 g6 8. O-O Bg7
9. Re1 Nh6 (9... Nf6 10. c3 $1 $14) 10. Na3 O-O 11. Nc4 Rb8 {Black prepares
b7-b5} 12. a4 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. Nfe5 $1 (14. Nce5 Bb7 $11) 14... Nxe5 15.
Nxe5 Bb7 16. Bxb7 Rxb7 17. Nc6 Qe8 (17... Qd6 18. Ra6 $16) 18. Qf3 Rc7 19. Ra6
$14) (5... f6 $6 6. d4 $1 cxd4 7. exd4 Bg4 8. Bg2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Qd7 11.
Qe2 Nge7 12. h3 Bf5 13. c4 (13. g4 $6 Be4 $1 $15) 13... O-O 14. Nc3 $16 {
now that the e4 square is protected White wants to continue with g3-g4 and
it's not clear how to deal with Black against this problem}) (5... Bg4 6. Bg2
Nf6 (6... e5 $6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 $14 {White can continue with g4-Nc3-000
enjoying his bishops pair}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O e6 9. Nc3 $5 $146 {I like this
idea: we want to play Ne2 next and then chose between Nf4, gaining the bishops
pair, or c2-c4, where Black's d5-d4 will not be possible anymore} Bd6 10. Ne2
O-O 11. Nf4 (11. c4 $5 {also possible as now Black cannot play d5-d4 anymore})
11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {engine evaluates as equal, but I would take White}) 6. c4
$1 {now that Black cannot answer with d5-d4 we should definitely go for this} (
6. Bg2 e5 $1) 6... dxc4 {the only logical continuation} 7. bxc4 {of course we
take back with the pawn, as our bishop already belongs to the g2 square} Nf6 (
7... Bf5 $6 {to early: comparing to 7...Nf6, 8.Bg2 Bf5, now after Nh4! Black
will not be able to play Bd3 as our bishop is still on f1} 8. Nh4 $1 $146 Be4
9. f3 Bg6 10. Nc3 Nf6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. f4 $16 {Bg2-Qe2-00 next}) (7... e5 $6 {
strategically dubious as now the d5 square weakness will be chronic} 8. Nc3 Nf6
9. d3 Be7 10. Bg2 O-O (10... Be6 11. Ng5 $1 Bf5 12. Nge4 $16) 11. Nd5 $1 Qd6
12. O-O Nxd5 13. cxd5 Qxd5 14. Nxe5 Qe6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qc2 $14 {nobody
would be happy to play like this with Black: the 'c' pawns are a very big
target}) 8. Bg2 Bf5 9. Qa4 $5 $146 (9. O-O $5 Bd3 10. Re1 e6 (10... Bxc4 $2 11.
d4 $16) 11. Qb3 $13 {could also be considered}) (9. Nh4 $6 {now would be wrong
as Black can answer with Bd3} Bd3 $1 $15) (9. d4 cxd4 10. exd4 e6 11. O-O Rd8
12. Qb3 (12. Qa4 Be7 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Rac1 Ne4 $11 15. Rfd1 Nxd2 16. Rxd2 Be4
$11) 12... Be7 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Rac1 Ne4 15. Rfd1 Nxd2 16. Rxd2 Na5 (16... Be4
17. d5 $1 $16 {comparing to 12.Qa4, now thanks to 12.Qb3 White will be able to
play Qe3 next}) 17. Qc3 b5 18. c5 (18. cxb5 $5 Qxc3 19. Bxc3 Nc4 20. bxa6 $5
Nxd2 21. Nxd2 $36 {is also very interesting, as now Black should find a few
accurate moves in order to equalize}) 18... Nc4 19. Re2 $14 {we have reached a
strategically complex position, where the engine evaluates +0,30, but objectively
all the fight is still ahead}) 9... Nd7 {very logical, against Ne5 ideas} (9...
e6 $6 10. Ne5 $16) (9... O-O-O 10. O-O $40 {too risky for Black: White will
continue with d2-d4 with a potential very strong attack}) 10. O-O Nb6 11. Qb3
Na5 12. Be5 $1 {the key justification of 9.Qa4} Nxb3 13. Bxc7 Nxa1 14. Bxb6 e6
15. g4 $1 Bd3 (15... Bxg4 $2 16. Rc1 Bf5 17. Ne1 $16 {Nc3 next}) 16. Rc1 Nc2
17. Ne5 Nb4 18. Nc3 Bd6 19. Nxd3 Nxd3 20. Rb1 $14 {[%emt 0:00:09] We have full
compensation for the exchange, and personally, I would be very happy to play
this very interesting position. Even the engine evaluates +0,20 with perfect play
from Black's side. Still, if somebody doesn't feel comfortable playing
exchange down, he could pick one of the other 2 moves at move}) 4. Nf3 {
remember: when Black plays with 3...Nf6 and without Nc6, White will be able to
play the move c2-c4 as Black cannot answer anymore with the move d5-d4} e6 (
4... g6 5. c4 $1 Bg7 (5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 $5 {I really like
this idea: we want to prevent the Bg4 ideas, and then slowly play Qe2-Rd1-d4} (
8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nd2 Nc6 $11) (8. Qe2 a6 9. a4 Bg4 $1 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
Qxf3 Nc6 $11) 8... Nc6 9. Qe2 a6 (9... b6 10. Rd1 Bb7 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4
13. Bxd4 Qc7 14. Na3 a6 15. Rac1 $14 {Qb2 next}) 10. a4 $36 {we will continue
with Rd1-d4, and at least from the practical perspective, it is hard to play
here with Black in this new position that was never reached in over-the-board
games}) 6. cxd5 Qxd5 (6... O-O $6 {this logical move is already a mistake, and
many very strong players have fallen into it!} 7. Bxf6 $3 {Black had counted on
the assurance that after castling kingside, his bishop on g7 would be defended
and he could recapture the d5 pawn with Nxd5 on the next move. However,
following the remarkable 7.Bxf6, he quickly realizes that his strategy is
fundamentally flawed.} exf6 (7... Bxf6 8. Nc3 $14) 8. Nc3 f5 9. Bc4 Nd7 10. O-O
a6 11. a4 $14 {Black will not be able to take back the pawn anymore, and in a
favourable moment we will continue with d2-d4}) 7. Nc3 {now again Black needs
to be precise} Qd8 $1 (7... Qf5 $2 {a common mistake} 8. e4 $1 Qd7 (8... Nxe4
$2 9. Bd3 $16) 9. Bb5 Nc6 10. Na4 $16) (7... Qh5 $6 8. Nb5 $1 Na6 9. Be2 O-O
10. Rc1 $14) 8. Ne4 {and now Black needs to find 8...b6} b6 $1 (8... Nbd7 {
is the most natural move, but here White has an advantage:} 9. Qc2 b6 10. Ng3
Bb7 11. h4 $1 h5 12. Ng5 O-O 13. f4 $16 {Bc4 next}) 9. b4 $5 $146 cxb4 10.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bxf6 exf6 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qxb4 Nc6 14. Qb2 $14 {/= the
evaluation of this position is between more pleasant for White and equal. But
I hope you agree that Black had to be very precise in order to reach this
point!}) (4... Bg4 {again, this is typically bad when Black play the d5+c5
systems} 5. h3 Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Qxf3 $14) 6. g4 Bg6 7. Ne5 Nbd7 (7... Nfd7 8.
Nxg6 hxg6 9. Qf3 $1 e6 10. c4 $1 $16) 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Bg2 e6 10. c4 $16) 5. c4
$1 {now we will go for this as Black is not able to answer with d5-d4} Nc6 6.
cxd5 exd5 {This position is thoroughly analyzed in Course 1.Nf3 for Black part
1, authored by GM Pier Luigi Basso, one of the two authors of this course. In
the final chapter of this database, the author will elucidate the possible
ways to tackle this position when playing as White.} *

