{[%evp 0,37,29,-13,-25,-25,-21,-12,-9,-1,21,11,11,-2,25,15,13,29,29,29,29,29,
29,16,40,37,39,40,42,36,43,16,41,18,23,25,19,24,17,18]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3.
e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 {Before going into Black's main set-up, with 4...Be7, we need
to analyze this last sideline} 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3 c6 {[%emt 0:00:09] This is
usually played by the semi-slav players. I have played this position myself a
lot of times from the Black side. Now I will share with you my Black-side
preparation and my main worries. All others Black's 6th move will be analyzed
together with Baadur in the next Chapter} 7. Be2 e5 {This has always been my
main move playing from the Black side} (7... dxc4 8. bxc4 e5 {This line has
never been particularly popular from Black's perspective. Personally, I
believe it's a matter of taste; perhaps with thorough analysis, someone
playing as Black could increase his chances of securing a draw. However, I
view it as a somewhat disheartening line for Black, akin to adopting a
"Petroff style" approach where the primary objective seems to be playing for a
draw.} 9. d4 exd4 10. exd4 Bg4 11. O-O Nbd7 12. h3 Bh5 13. Nh4 Bxe2 14. Qxe2
$14) (7... Nbd7 {this is something that I always wanted to avoid with Black} 8.
Qc2 Re8 (8... b6 9. Rg1 $1 {White starts to play with g2-g4 and I have always
felt that this direction is too risky for Black, for example:} Bb7 10. g4 Qe7 (
10... e5 11. g5 Ne8 12. h4 Nc7 {1-0 Giri,A (2776)-Michiels,B (2536) FRA-chT
Top 12 Montpellier 2015 (3.1)} 13. h5 $1 Ne6 14. O-O-O $16) 11. g5 Ne8 12. h4
$16) 9. O-O (9. Rg1 $6 {now this is not the right plan as Black can play e5} e5
$1 10. g4 d4 $17 {White is simply not in time}) 9... b6 {this is probably
Black's best move order} (9... e5 10. cxd5 cxd5 (10... Nxd5 11. Ne4 Bc7 12. Ng3
N7f6 13. a3 a5 14. d3 $14 {White has achieved a long game: he will continue
with Rad1 and then eventually e4 and d4, and it's a little bit unpleasant to
play this from the Black side}) 11. Nb5 Bb8 12. Rfc1 $16 {Nc7 next}) 10. d4 {
Now, White should consider transposing into an Anti-Meran setup, but this only
requires familiarity with this particular line. Naturally, we cannot delve too
deeply into this position here, as doing so would necessitate entire chapters.
However, I will outline a few critical lines that should suffice to begin
playing this position. Of course, for those interested, further analysis of
these lines can be pursued independently. Perhaps one day, I may even develop
a comprehensive course on the Anti-Meran, an opening I feel particularly
well-versed in!} Bb7 11. a4 $5 {the modern trend is to include a4-a5 (if Black
doesn't play a5, White will continue with a4-a5 himself). The main idea is
that when Black plays c6-c5 at some moment, the b5 square will be weak.
True, also White's b4 square is weak, but White already has a Nc3 ready to
jump there, while Black's knight for the moment is still on d7.} a5 12. Rad1
Qe7 13. Bd3 (13. e4 $5 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Rad8 (15... Nf6 16. Qe3 c5
17. Ne5 $14) 16. Ne5 $13) 13... Rad8 14. h3 h6 15. Rfe1 Bb4 {pinning Nc3
against e3-e4 White's ideas} 16. Re2 {unpinning Nc3!} c5 17. cxd5 {This is one
of the critical positions. In general White is not risking much, but you could
continue to analyze by yourself. I have tried to equalize here with Black, but
somehow I have found some problems after all 17...Bxc3, 17...exd5, and 17...
cxd4}) 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 {here I tried to play both 9...e4 and 9...Nc6. Now
I will share with you what I think are the main problems of both set-ups} Nc6 (9...
e4 10. Nfd4 Be5 11. Ne6 Bxe6 (11... fxe6 {Black takes back with the pawn
because he wants to be able to play Nc6-e5 next} 12. Bxe5 Nc6 {I have reached
this position in my game against Alanic in June 2020} 13. Bb2 $1 (13. Bc7 Qd7
14. Bg3 e5 $13 {Alanic, X - Basso, P.L. June 2020} 15. d4 exd3 16. Qxd3 Ne4 17.
a3 Qf7 18. f3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Bf5 20. Qd2 Rfd8 21. Rc1 a6 22. Nc3 Na5 23. Bd1 d4
24. e4 dxc3 25. Qxc3 Rdc8 26. Qxa5 Rxc1 27. exf5 Qxb3 28. Qd2 Qxa3 29. O-O Qc5+
30. Kh2 Kh8 31. f6 gxf6 32. Rf2 Rxd1 33. Qxd1 Qxf2 34. Qd6 Re8 35. Qxf6+ Kg8
36. Qg5+ Kf7 37. Qf5+ Ke7 38. Qxe5+ Kd7 39. Qf5+ Kd8 40. Qf7 Qb6 41. f4 Qc7 {
0-1 Alanic,X (2249)-Basso,P (2600) Cattolica op 7th 2020 (5)}) 13... e5 14. Ba3
a6 $1 {my preparation was relaying in this move} (14... Rf7 15. Nd6 Rd7 16.
Nxc8 Rxc8 17. Rc1 $14) 15. Nd6 (15. Bxf8 axb5 16. Bc5 b6 17. Bxb5 Na7 18. Bxb6
Qxb6 19. Be2 Nc6 $13) 15... Qa5 16. Qc1 Rd8 17. O-O Nb4 18. Nxc8 Raxc8 19. Bxb4
Qxb4 20. Qb2 $14 {White is simply slightly better}) 12. Bxe5 Nc6 13. Bb2 $14)
10. Nxd6 Qxd6 11. d4 e4 12. Ne5 Nd7 {Black needs to be fast in challenging Ne5}
13. Nxc6 bxc6 (13... Qxc6 $6 14. O-O Nf6 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Rc1 Qe6 17. Qc2 $14 {
White will play Qc7 next and this is something that Black isn't happy to play})
14. Qd2 $1 {White wants to play Qa5} a5 {After playing 14...Re8 in October
2020, just a few months later, I encountered this line again against my good
friend Paolo Formento. Having learned from the previous encounter involving
Qa5, I was now prepared. This time, I opted for 14...a5, denying White's queen
access to the a5 square} (14... Re8 15. Qa5 Qg6 {½-½ Leisch,L (2394)-Basso,P
(2570) Banicky Kahanec Bojnice 2020 (4) was reached in my game against one of
the young Austrian theoreticians Leisch Lukas} 16. g4 $1 $14 {would have been
very unpleasant for Black} (16. O-O Nf8 17. Rfc1 Bh3 18. Bf1 Bd7 19. Qc7 Rec8
20. Qg3 Qxg3 21. hxg3 a5 22. Ba3 h5 23. Be2 g6 24. f3 Re8 25. Kf2 Kg7 26. Rc3
Ne6 27. Bd6 f6 28. a4 Nd8 29. Rb1 Nf7 30. Bc5 Reb8 31. Bd1 Bc8 32. Bc2 Bf5 33.
f4 Bc8 34. b4 axb4 35. Rxb4 Ba6 36. Rcb3 Rxb4 37. Rxb4 Nh6 38. Bd1 Ng4+ 39.
Bxg4 hxg4 40. Rb6 Kg8 41. Bd6 Kf7 42. Rb8 Rxb8 43. Bxb8 Ke6 44. Ba7 c5 45. dxc5
f5 46. Bb8 Kd7 47. Be5 Kc6 48. Bd4 Bc4 49. Ke1 Bb3 50. a5 Kb5 51. c6 Kxc6 52.
Kd2 Bc4 53. Kc3 Bf1 54. Bb6 Bxg2 55. Kd4 Bf1 56. Ke5 Ba6 57. Kf6 Bc8 58. Kxg6
Kb5 59. Kf6 Ka6 60. Ke5 Kb7 61. Kxd5 Ka8 62. Kc5 Kb7 63. Kd6 Kb8 64. Bd4 Kb7
65. Be5 Ka8 66. Kc7 Ba6 67. Kb6 Bb7 68. a6 Bc8 69. a7 Bb7 70. Bd4 Bc8 71. Kc7
Ba6 72. Kd7 Bb7 73. Kc7 Ba6 74. Kd7 Bb7 75. Kc7 {½-½ Leisch,L (2394)-Basso,P
(2570) Banicky Kahanec Bojnice 2020 (4)})) 15. a4 $1 (15. Bc3 {is the move
that was played against me, but now Black achieves a very nice position, and I
won a very nice game} Qc7 16. O-O Re8 $1 {the key plan, Black wants to play
Re6-Rh6 with a very strong attack on the kingside} 17. a4 Re6 18. b4 Rh6 $17 {
Formento, P - Basso, P. L. December 2020} 19. g3 axb4 20. Bxb4 Nf6 21. f4 exf3
22. Bxf3 Rg6 23. Bg2 h5 24. Rf4 Ba6 25. e4 dxe4 26. Bxe4 Nxe4 27. Rxe4 c5 28.
Bxc5 Bb7 29. Qe2 Qc6 30. Re1 Qxe4 31. Qxe4 Bxe4 32. Rxe4 Re6 33. Rxe6 fxe6 34.
Kf2 Kf7 35. Kf3 Rxa4 36. h4 Ra1 37. Bd6 Rf1+ 38. Ke4 Re1+ 39. Kf4 Rf1+ 40. Ke4
g6 41. Be5 Ke7 42. Bb8 Kd7 43. Ke5 Rb1 44. Ba7 Rb7 45. Bc5 Rb3 46. Kf4 Kc6 47.
Ke5 Rxg3 48. Kxe6 g5 49. hxg5 h4 50. Bd6 Rxg5 51. Be7 Rg6+ 52. Ke5 h3 53. d5+
Kd7 54. Kd4 {0-1 Formento,P (2315)-Basso,P (2561) Bassano del Grappa Vergani
Cup 5th 2020 (5)}) 15... Re8 16. Ba3 Qg6 {is better according to the engine, but
now Black loses his main plan Re6-Rh6:} (16... Qc7 17. O-O-O $3 {the right
approach from the White side} Rb8 18. Kb2 Qb6 19. Qc3 Ba6 20. Rd2 Bxe2 21. Rxe2
$14 {Black finds himself in an uncomfortable position: White has the option to
play f3, followed by exf3-gxf3. Subsequently, White can maneuver the rooks to
g1 and g2, and after Black plays g6, White can proceed with moves like h4-h5.
This sequence of moves creates a highly challenging situation for Black.}) 17.
O-O Ba6 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 19. Rfb1 $14 {at some moment White will play b3-b4, with
a completely risk-free position that Black needs to defend carefully} *

