{[%evp 0,29,20,-21,-18,-18,-14,-14,-2,-2,5,10,10,11,26,4,28,18,16,16,4,26,25,
21,25,29,33,36,34,46,29,29]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. c4 O-O
6. Nc3 {In the last Chapter we have seen 6...c6, now let's analyze others
Black's options when he doesn't want to go for a semi-slav set-up} Re8 {
This is very popular nowadays} (6... c5 7. cxd5 {this is safer than 7.g4, but
Black has a solid position:} (7. g4 $5 {1-0 Giri,A (2749)-Warmerdam,M (2625)
Tata Steel-A 86th Wijk aan Zee 2024 (13) could also be interesting: it was
played in the very recent game Giri-Warmerdam. We will speak more about it in
the Model Games section.}) 7... exd5 8. d4 Nc6 9. Be2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11.
Qxd4 Re8 12. O-O Be5 13. Qd2 d4 14. exd4 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Bxd4 16. Bf3 $14 {
White has a pleasant endgame. We will speak about it in the model games
section.}) (6... b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nb5 $1 {a typical White's idea in the 4...
Bd6 variation} Be7 9. Be5 Ne8 (9... Na6 10. Be2 c6 11. Nbd4 Qd7 {against Nf5}
12. Rc1 c5 13. Bb5 Qg4 $2 (13... Qd8 14. Nc6 Qd7 15. d4 Bb7 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17.
O-O $14) 14. h3 Qg6 15. Nc6 $16) 10. Rc1 c5 11. Bxb8 a6 $3 $146 {the only
solution} (11... Rxb8 12. Nxa7 $14) 12. Be5 axb5 13. Bxb5 Rxa2 14. Ra1 Rxa1 15.
Qxa1 $14 {slightly better for White but objectively not terrible for Black}) (
6... a6 7. d4 b6 8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. bxc4 c5 12. d5 exd5 13.
Nxd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 b5 15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Nh4 Re8 (16... Be5 17. Nf5 g6 (17... c4
18. Ba3 Re8 19. Rad1 Nc5 20. e4 Nd3 21. f4 Bb8 22. Kh1 Qf6 23. d6 Bxe4 24. Ne7+
Rxe7 25. dxe7 Qd4 (25... Qe6 26. Rfe1 f5 27. Rxd3 cxd3 28. Qxd3 Qxe7 29. Bxe4
fxe4 30. Rxe4 Qb7)) 18. d6) 17. Bxg7) 7. Nb5 Be7 (7... Bf8 $2 {some people may
think that the idea of 6...Re8 was exactly to free the f8 square for the black
squares bishop, but in fact, this is a mistake} 8. Bxf6 $1 {and Black is not
able to recapture with the queen as c7 is hanging} gxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 (9... a6
10. Nc3 exd5 11. Bd3 d4 12. Ne2 dxe3 13. dxe3 $14) 10. Bd3 $16) 8. Be5 Na6 9.
Be2 c6 10. Nc3 Nc5 {the most common move} (10... Nd7 11. Bg3 Nac5 12. Qc2 Nf6
13. d4 Nce4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bd3 $14) (10... Ne4 {this is the engine
recommendation} 11. Qc2 f6 12. Bg3 Nb4 13. Qb1 e5 $1 {Strong grandmasters like
Jules Moussard and Andrey Esipenko have followed the engine's recommendation
and have reached this point} (13... f5 $6 14. a3 Na6 15. Qb2 $14) 14. cxd5 (14.
a3 {has been played by Santos Latasa, but after} Bf5 $3 $146 {I am not sure
who is fighting for the initiative}) 14... Nxc3 15. dxc3 Nxd5 16. Bd3 $1 h6 17.
O-O Nxc3 $1 {the most critical and the only equalizer for Black} 18. Bc4+ Kh8
19. Qc2 {It is amazing to note that both Keymer and Esipenko knew up to this
moment, and it was just a blitz game!!} b5 $1 $146 (19... Nd5 {the move played
by Esipenko, a very human move but not the most precise} 20. Qg6 Be6 {
Keymer-Esipenko biel blitz 2022} 21. Nxe5 $1 $146 fxe5 22. Qxe6 Bf6 23. Qf5 $14
) 20. Bxe5 bxc4 (20... fxe5 $2 21. Nxe5 $18) 21. Bxc3 $11 {the position is
around equal}) 11. Qc2 Ncd7 (11... a5 12. h3 $5 $14 {I like this move, so that
after Ncd7 White will always have the h2 square to retreat his bishop}) 12. Bg3
dxc4 (12... Bb4 {has been played just a few days ago} 13. O-O Qe7 {
Alonso-Shuvalova 2024. Now the engine wants to continue with dxc4-Bxc4-b5, that's
why I like the prophylactic move} 14. a4 $14 {where Black is solid, but for
sure a little bit worse}) 13. bxc4 (13. Bxc4 b5 $1 14. Be2 Bb7 $11) 13... b6 {
Donchenko-Tabatabei 2023} 14. O-O $146 Bb7 (14... c5 $4 15. Nb5 $18) 15. d4 $14
{[%cal Re7b4,Gc3e4,Rc6c5,Gd4d5] With a very pleasant positional advantage, we
are ready to meet c5 with d5! and Bb4 with Ne4.} *

