{[%evp 0,29,20,-32,-14,-14,-14,-23,-2,-4,8,6,6,-2,29,0,9,-17,-20,-16,-10,-19,
-12,-39,-26,-27,-21,-17,-17,-41,29,4]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Be7
5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3 {This is what we will call the "Main system". Now Black has a
few different choices. The main ones are 6...b6 which we will analyze in
Chapter 11 and 6...c5 that we will analyze in Chapter 12. We will deal with
all the other moves in this chapter} dxc4 (6... Nbd7 7. Qc2 c6 8. d4 {, as we
will see in the notes after 6...c6, we are happy to transpose into an
Anti-Meran position because Black has already committed to the move Be7} b6 9.
Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O {it is known that here Black cannot achieve full equality.
Of course, the Anti-Meran is a very big topic and it would require entire
chapters to be analyzed in detail. For those players who don't have too much
experience in these positions, I suggest checking some typical games. The good
news is that you don't need to deal with the very big amounts of theory of the
Anti-Meran, but you just need to play this exact position that is not
theoretical and it is simply slightly better for White. You can check to start
the game Kramnik-Van Wely}) (6... c6 7. d4 $1 {we are happy now to transpose
into an Anti-Meran position, as Black has already committed his bishop to e7 
(it stays much better on d6)} Nbd7 8. Bd3 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qe2 c5 11. cxd5
exd5 12. Rfd1 $14) (6... a5 7. d4 $1 {again, the move 6...a5 is not useful if
we transpose into 1.d4 systems} b6 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qc2 $14) 7. bxc4
c5 {Black has decided to go for this structural transformation. In general, I
am happy when I am playing with an extra central pawn. In addition here, White
has some interesting dynamical possibilities.} 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. a3 $5 {against
all Nb4 annoying jumps} b6 10. Be2 {defending Nf3 before going for g2-g4 ideas!
} Bb7 11. Rg1 $1 {the best plan, also according to the engine. In practice here it
is very hard to play from the Black side} Na5 (11... Nd7 12. g4 Nce5 13. Nxe5
Nxe5 14. O-O-O a6 15. f4 Ng6 16. f5 Nh4 {1-0 Artemiev, V (2704)-Nakamura, H 
(2736) Chessable Masters KO chess24.com INT rapid 2021 (1.21) Here Artemiev
has played the immediate Ne4, but I suggest starting with} 17. fxe6 $1 $146
fxe6 18. Ne4 $16) (11... a6 12. g4 Nd7 13. g5 f5 14. gxf6 Bxf6 {
Rakhmanov-Shuvalova 2021} 15. Ne4 $1 $146 Bxb2 16. Neg5 $1 g6 17. Qxb2 Qe7 18.
h4 $40 {1-0 Feuerstein,M-Maioriello,G (1574) W-ch WS/O/1370 email ICCF email
2021 here there was only one correspondence game played in 2021, where White
has won convincingly. For sure this is not a good sign for the Black side!})
12. d3 Ne8 13. g4 Nd6 14. g5 f5 (14... Nf5 $2 {already losing, and it has been
played by a very strong GM like Sergey Movsesian in a classical game in 2018.
This shows how difficult is to play this position from the Black side} 15. Ne4
$16 {1-0 Malakhov, V (2666)-Movsesian, S (2645) CRO-chT1A 27th Biograd 2018 (3.
51)}) 15. O-O-O $14 {I really like here White's possibilities. One possible
plan suggested by the engine is to continue with Nb1 and Qc3! creating some nasty
threats against the Black's king} *

