{[%evp 0,33,18,-28,-18,-13,-7,-13,-4,1,9,3,14,14,28,11,4,-8,6,26,20,20,20,20,
22,24,20,23,55,20,55,52,60,58,78,68]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Be7
5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3 b6 {this move leads to a strategically complex position and
it's important to understand the spirit of the arizing positions in order to
know how to play them} 7. cxd5 {Typically, this is a good reaction when Black
opts for b7-b6 with the pawn still on c7. Why? Because if Black recaptures
with exd5, when he will later play Bb7 it will be more passive. How does this
differ from the configuration with pawns on e6 and c4? In that scenario,
Black's inability to play dxc4 to activate the bishop becomes evident} exd5 (
7... Nxd5 {Black can opt for Nxd5. Subsequently, if White responds with Nxd5,
Black has two potential strategies: - exd5. This move, in comparison to an
immediate exd5, allows Black to exchange a pair of knights. We'll delve into
who might benefit more from this exchange shortly. - Qxd5. Here, Black keeps
the a8-h1 diagonal open for his Bb7. However, this recapture presents two
drawbacks: A dynamical problem: Black's queen on d5 becomes vulnerable,
potentially allowing White to gain tempo. A positional problem: White will
possess an extra central pawn. Nevertheless, when White eventually plays d2-d4,
Black aims to counter with c7-c5, introducing tension into the center. So we
will have to check again what happens from a concrete point of view.} 8. Nxd5
Qxd5 (8... exd5 {Now the challenge for White is to find in which direction the
exchange of the knights is favourable for him} 9. Be2 $1 {In this direction
the absence of Nc3 and Nf6 is in White's favour. To understand better the
reason check the notes in the variation 9...Bb7} (9. g3 {This is how we will
play in the 7...exd5 variation. Here, without Nc3 and Nf6, I think we
shouldn't go in this direction. The main point is that Black will have the
Bf6 idea} c5 10. Bg2 Ba6 11. d3 Nc6 12. O-O Bf6 $5 {Black has this additional
idea of Bf6 (which, of course, becomes more challenging to execute when he
still has the knight on f6), and I believe it oversimplifies the position too
much.}) 9... c5 (9... Bb7 {here we can follow a game of the biggest expert of
these positions: Vincent Keymer} 10. O-O Nd7 11. Rc1 {I encourage you to note
the difference: with the exchange of Nc3 and Nf6, when White plays Qc2,
pressure on the c7 pawn intensifies swiftly. Additionally, White gains Nd4
possibilities, directly threatening Nc6 due to the absence of Nc3. Overall, in
this position, it proves advantageous for White to have exchanged the pair of
knights} Re8 12. Qc2 Rc8 13. Qf5 Bf6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. d4 Qd6 16. Ne5 c5 {
1-0 Keymer, V (2591)-Grigorian, S (2458) GER-chT Online Liga Playoffs Playchess.
com INT rapid 2021 (2.3)} 17. Qf4 $5 $14 {in the game Vincent has played 17.
Bd3, maybe 17.Qf4 would have created some more problems for Black}) 10. O-O Bb7
(10... Nc6 11. d4 a5 {played by Fabiano Caruana} 12. Bb5 $5 Na7 13. Bd3 {
White managed to improve a little bit his Be2, which could be more active from
the d3 square} Nc6 14. h3 $5 $14 {against Bg4 ideas}) 11. d4 Nd7 12. Rc1 $14 {
typically slightly better for White}) 9. Qc2 {putting pressure on the
undefended c7 pawn} Qc6 $1 $146 {the best according to engine} (9... Ba6 {
White can now accept the sacrificed pawn} 10. Qxc7 Bxf1 11. Qxe7 Bxg2 $2 {
would be Black's idea, but it simply doesn't work} (11... Nc6 12. Qg5 Qxg5 13.
Nxg5 Bd3 14. f3 $14) 12. Rg1 Qxf3 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qg5+ Kh8 15. Rxg2 $18) (
9... Bb7 $2 10. Qxc7 Bd6 11. Qc3 f6 12. Bc4 $16) (9... c5 $6 10. Bd3 f5 11. e4
Qd8 12. exf5 exf5 13. Bc4+ Kh8 14. d4 $16 {White's bishops are too strong}) 10.
Bc4 Ba6 11. Rc1 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Qxc4 13. Rxc4 c5 14. Ke2 Nd7 15. d4 Rfc8 16. Rhc1
$14 {White has a pleasant and slightly-better endgame}) 8. g3 {The most
frequently played move here has been 8.d4. However, I prefer to steer clear of
Colle transpositions whenever feasible. Typically, in such positions, Black
holds a solid position objectively, and opponents often possess greater
experience from the Black side, nullifying any practical advantage we might
hope to gain.} Bb7 (8... c5 {Black can try to play c5 immediately, savind a
tempo on Bb7 that might go in some cases directly to a6} 9. Bg2 Ba6 {this is a
little bit more annoying because compared to the previous line we are not
able to play our ideal moves 00 and Re1. Fortunately, it has been played only
in 2 games} (9... Nc6 10. O-O Ba6 (10... Bb7 {transposes in the main line of
this chapter}) 11. Re1 Nb4 12. Ne5 $1 {might look a little bit scary, but we
will play d2-d4 next and Black doesn't have a way to exploit our temporary
light-squares weakness} Bd6 (12... Nd3 {in fact this is the best according to
the engine and it means that Black is just slightly worse} 13. Nxd3 Bxd3 14. Ne2 $14
{Nf4 next}) 13. d4 $16) 10. d3 Nc6 11. O-O Rc8 (11... Nb4 {don't worry, Black
is not in time:} 12. Ne5 Bd6 13. a3 $1 Bxe5 14. axb4 {and Ba6 is hanging} cxb4
15. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 16. Bxe5 $16) 12. a3 {preventing Nb4 ideas once-forever} Re8
13. Re1 Bf8 14. Ne2 {we want to continue with some useful moves like Rc1,
maybe Bh3, and eventually d4 or b4. This is a new position that needs some
practice to be understood completely. The initial feeling, also according to
the engine, is that it's a little bit easier to play from the White side}) (8...
Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O {we have played g2-g3 but that's more a useful move
for us then a weakness} c5 (10... Nc5 11. Ne5 Bd6 12. Nb5 $14) 11. d4 Nc7 12.
Qd3 Qd7 13. Rfd1 Rfd8 14. Rac1 $14) 9. Bg2 c5 {this is the most common
treatment of the position in practice. Black wants to develop his Nb8 on c6} (
9... d4 $6 {Black hopes that after} 10. exd4 {he will be able to take back the
d4 pawn, and then he will have a better pawn structure. The problem for him is
that he will not be in time to regain the d4 pawn!} Nc6 11. Ne2 {yes, our pawn
structure d2-d4 is not ideal, but still, we have a pawn up that is controlling
some important squares and it's not easy for Black to understand how to take
it back} Nb4 {Black tries to play somehow for the d3 square} 12. O-O Nd3 13.
Bc3 c5 14. Ne1 $1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 $14 {at some moment Black will play cxd4, and
we will have an extra d2 pawn. According to the engine Black's compensation is
worth half a pawn, not a full one. So White keeps his chances and will enjoy
his extra pawn and the +0,50 evaluation}) (9... Nbd7 {we will se that after 9..
.c5 10.00, the move Nbd7 would not be so logical. Here it is different. In
general if Black wants to play with Nbd7 he shouldn't hurry with c7-c5} 10. O-O
{now both sides will make their own useful moves} Re8 11. Rc1 a6 12. Re1 {
when Black has already played a7-a6 this move is not compulsory, as Black will
not have Ba6 ideas anymore. Still, I like to include it} Nc5 {trying to improve
the knight transferring it on the e6 square} (12... Bf8 13. Ne2 Rc8 (13... g6
14. Nf4 Bg7 15. d3 a5 16. Re2 $14 {Rec2 next}) 14. Bh3 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal
Yh3c8] threatening Bxf6 where Black will have to take gxf6 because Qxf6 is
impossible due to Bxd7}) (12... Bd6 13. Ne2 Ne5 $6 {a strategically bad
exchange} 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. b4 $1 $14 {Black will not be able to
play c5 anymore and his c7 pawn will be a permanent weakness unless he
decides to play c7-c6 that has other evident problems ( Bb7 will be very very
passive...)}) 13. d3 Ne6 14. Re2 $5 Rc8 15. Rec2 c5 16. d4 Rc7 {Keymer-Liang
2021} 17. Na4 $5 $14) 10. O-O Nc6 {transposes in the main line of this chapter}
(10... d4 $6 {Black's development doesn't allow him to go for such concrete
ideas} 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Ne2 d3 13. Nf4 {now the d3 pawn is more a weakness
than a strength, for example:} Na6 14. Nxd3 $1 Qxd3 15. Ne5 $16) (10... Nbd7 {
it looks a little bit strange to play c7-c5 and then still develop Nb8 on d7.
Usually, this way of playing is not common at high level} 11. d4 Rc8 12. Qe2 Re8
13. Rfd1 Bf8 14. Rac1 $14 {White is just slightly better. A typical idea later
could be Ne1-Nd3 with future Nf4 ideas against the potentially weak d5 pawn})
11. d4 Rc8 (11... Ne4 12. dxc5 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 bxc5 14. Qd2 Qd6 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16.
Qb2 $5 Bf8 17. Rd2 $14 {Rad1 next and White's position is for sure more
pleasant to play}) 12. Rc1 Re8 13. Re1 {this little move is something that you
need to learn to play from the White side: - you can later think about Re2-Rd2
or Re2-Rec2 ideas - Black will not have some Ba6 annoying ideas against Rf1} ({
For example the immediate} 13. Ne2 {would be countered with} Ba6 $1 14. Re1 Nb4
$13) 13... Bf8 14. Ne2 Ne4 (14... Ba6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Nf4 $16) 15. Nf4 Ne7
16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Nd2 $14 *

