{[%evp 0,69,27,-17,-5,-5,-2,-2,7,1,16,-3,19,19,20,12,3,3,18,9,45,0,12,40,18,9,
20,20,20,20,38,40,20,28,29,31,24,40,46,46,46,53,41,54,51,49,49,49,56,52,52,53,
51,37,30,30,78,58,46,40,50,46,72,72,73,68,84,86,80,94,125,134]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2
Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3 c5 {by far the most common move in
the position} 7. cxd5 {Black now has two conceptually different options} exd5 (
7... Nxd5 8. Qc2 {now we want to play in a very dynamical way: h4-Ng5} Nc6 (
8... b6 9. h4 $5 Nb4 {for the engine it's very easy to play like this with
Black, but we know that it is not over the board} (9... h6 10. g4 Bb7 11. Nxd5
Bxd5 12. e4 Bb7 13. g5 $40) (9... Ba6 $2 {logical: Black wants to exchange the
light squares bishops, but it's a mistake!} 10. Ng5 $1 g6 11. Nxd5 exd5 12.
Nxh7 Kxh7 13. h5 f5 14. hxg6+ Kxg6 15. Qd1 $16 {maybe is even stronger} (15. g4
$16 {1-0 Krysa,L (2533)-Beukema,J (2299) Dieren op 2018 (9)})) 10. Qe4 N8c6 11.
Rd1 f5 12. Qb1 $36 {egnine shows 0.10, over the board White's practical
advantage should be bigger in my opinion, and, again, Black had to find a lot
of "engine-style" moves}) 9. a3 $5 {preventing all engine ideas of Ncb4 and
Ndb4. I want to see how our opponents will react now that they don't have
their engine-style ideas of Ncb4 or Ndb4 :)} ({after} 9. h4 {The engine
suggests moves like Ncb4-Ndb4, and I'd rather not contend with them,
especially if our opponent is simply following the engine by hitting the space
bar}) 9... b6 (9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 b6 11. h4 Bf6 (11... Bb7 12. Ng5 g6 13. Bc4
$16) 12. Ng5 g6 13. Ne4 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 f5 15. Bb5 Bd7 (15... Bb7 16. Ng5 $16)
16. Ng5 Qf6 17. f4 $14) (9... Bf6 10. h4 Nxc3 11. dxc3 h6 12. g4 Ne5 13. Nxe5
Bxe5 {Herberla-Kusa} 14. g5 $1 h5 15. f4 Bc7 16. Bd3 $16 {according to engine
White is just winning}) 10. h4 $1 f5 $1 {Black really needs to play this move,
against Ne4 ideas and closing the b1-h7 diagonal for the White queen} (10... h6
{a lot of players are playing like this with Black, but now White has the
advantage:} 11. g4 $1 Bb7 12. g5 h5 13. Rg1 Rc8 14. Ne4 $18) 11. d4 cxd4 (11...
Bb7 $2 {Adhiban-So} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Rd1 $16) (11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Bf6 13. Qc2
Bb7 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Bc4 Qe7 16. Ng5 $14) 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bc4 Qd6 14. Rd1
$14) 8. d4 (8. Rc1 $5 {could be an interesting alternative if you have the
feeling that your opponent knows everything after 8.d4} Nc6 (8... b6 9. d4 Bb7
10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O $14 {typical pleasant for White game}) (8... d4 9. Na4
dxe3 {1-0 Nakamura, H (2768)-So, W (2761) American Cup Champ Saint Louis 2023 (5.
4)} 10. dxe3 $5 $146 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Nc6 12. Ne5 $14 {our pieces are better
than our opponent's ones, and for this reason, we can try to play this endgame
that the engine evaluates +0,30}) 9. Na4 b6 10. d4 cxd4 {critical} (10... Ne4 11.
Bb5 Bb7 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. O-O $14) 11. Nxd4 (11. Rxc6 $2 Bb4+ $17) 11... Nxd4
$1 $146 (11... Bb4+ 12. Bc3 Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Bb7 {Shankland-Murzin 2023} 14. Nxc6
Bxc6 15. Qd4 $14) 12. Qxd4 Bd6 13. Be2 $14 {/= looks playable. This 8.Rc1
requires further practical tests as it has been played only in 11 games out of
700}) 8... Nc6 9. Be2 Ne4 $1 {Thanks to this move Black can fight for full
equality} (9... Be6 10. O-O {is something that we should welcome when playing
from the White side. At some point, we will enter into an isolated queen's
pawn (IQP) position—either after dxc5 or if Black plays cxd4—where Black
doesn't have ways for a complete equalization} Rc8 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Rc1 Qe7
13. h3 Rfd8 14. Bd3 $5 $14 {Ne2 next}) (9... Bg4 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O a6 12.
h3 $5 Bh5 (12... Be6 13. Bd3 $14 {Ne2 next}) 13. Nh4 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 $14 {
Nf3 next with a full control over the d4 square}) 10. dxc5 Bf6 11. Rc1 Qa5 12.
Nd4 Nxc5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. O-O Ne4 $1 (14... Bf5 $6 15. Na4 $1 Nxa4 16. Bxf6
gxf6 17. bxa4 Qb6 18. a5 Qxa5 19. Rxc6 Qxa2 20. Rxf6 Bg6 21. h4 $16 {½-½
Grebnev, A (2539)-Khubukshanov, E (2352) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 2024 (4)}) 15. Qc2
Nxc3 16. Bxc3 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Qxa2 18. Rc2 Qa3 19. Ra1 Qe7 20. Qxc6 Be6 {this
position has been reached in 12 games. Half of them has ended in a draw, while
in the other half, White has managed to win. This exactly shows the type of 
position: Black is solid but is suffering a bit from the practical point of
view} 21. Qc5 Qxc5 (21... Qb7 $6 22. Qd4 Qb6 23. b4 $1 Qxd4 24. exd4 Rfb8 25.
b5 $16 {1-0 (39) Ganguly, S (2627)-Maurizzi, M (2502) Tata Steel-B 84th Wijk aan
Zee 2022 (1)}) 22. Rxc5 Rfd8 23. b4 d4 $1 (23... Rdb8 $6 24. b5 Rb7 25. Kf1
Rab8 26. Ke1 Rc8 27. Rxc8+ Bxc8 28. Rc1 Be6 29. Kd2 $16 {1-0 Jacobson, A (2446)
-Ahmad, K (2285) Sitges Sunway op 10th 2023 (8)}) 24. exd4 Rxd4 25. b5 {of
course engine will hold, but in a practical game White is pressing: even a
strong GM like Daniele Vocaturo wasn't able to hold this endgame against the
young Vincent Keymer in the European Championship 2021} Rd2 26. Bf3 Rad8 27. h3
R2d7 28. Rc3 Bd5 29. Bg4 Be6 30. Be2 Rd2 31. Bf3 Rb2 32. Bc6 g6 33. Rxa7 {
at some moment we reach a position like this where the engine confidently shows 0.
00, but over the board Black must find a good move to create counterplay.
Daniele didn't manage to do it:} Rd1+ 34. Kh2 Rxf2 $4 {decisive mistake} 35. b6
$18 {Keymer-Vocaturo European Championship 2021} *

