{[%evp 0,34,20,20,20,20,18,-3,0,-4,-10,-10,-7,-4,-4,-11,-10,-2,20,22,14,43,44,
61,61,6,57,-4,-4,-1,2,3,3,-1,-6,-3,-5] In chapter 7 we have concluded with a
position that was extensively analyzed in my course "1.Nf3 full repertoire for
Black, part 1". I am fully convinced that I have offered a rock-solid
repertoire for the Black side, and now I must give you an idea of how to play
with White against it. First of all, not all your opponents will be aware of
the suggestions I gave in my course, and that's unfortunate for them and for
me, but not for you! After long thinking, I will suggest you go for one of
the less known lines, played in the game Aronian-Pragg. We'll speak about it
in this chapter and I have also attacked you with the model game Aronian-Pragg that
I have analyzed for the "1.Nf3 full repertoire for Black, part 1"} 1. Nf3 d5 2.
e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 {[%emt 0:00:07] This is the
position where we have stopped in Chapter} 7. Nc3 $5 {only 50 games out of
2000, but a very interesting move in my opinion. Here I suggest 7...d4 for the
Black side, but of course we should check also other moves} ({the problem of} 
7. d4 {is Black's typical reaction} cxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 Bb4+ $1 {taking profit of
White is behind in development. In my course for the Black side I am
explaining this extensively in the model game Spoelman-Fridman, which I am also
attaching to this database}) 7... d4 $1 (7... Bd6 8. d4 $1 {comparing to 7.d4,
now Black doesn't have his typical reaction cxd4-Nxd4-Bb4+} cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O
10. Be2 {we can just play an IQP position} Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Re8 12. O-O Be5 13.
Qd2 Bg4 (13... d4 14. exd4 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Bxd4 {we have transposed into
Vitiugov-Wojtaszek that is analyzed in the model games section}) 14. Bxg4 Nxg4
15. h3 Nf6 16. Rfd1 $14 {Keymer-Aronian}) (7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. Rc1 Bd6 10.
Be2 O-O 11. O-O $14 {d2-d4 next}) (7... Be7 8. d4 O-O 9. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:12]
transposes into Chapter}) 8. Na4 Bd7 {my suggestion in "1.Nf3 full repertoire
for Black, part 1"} (8... d3 $6 9. Rc1 b6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Rc3 Nb4 12. Qb1 $16
) (8... Be7 9. Rc1 (9. Bb5 $5 Bd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 {playable for White.
Black always needs to think about Bxc6-Bxc6 exd4. If he decides to go for dxe3,
then after dxe3 White has a pleasant position}) 9... Qa5 $1 (9... dxe3 $6 10.
fxe3 (10. dxe3 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 {also possible, going into a slightly better
endgame. White will play Ne5 on the next move}) 10... b6 $1 $146 (10... Qd5 $6
11. Bc4 Qh5 12. O-O O-O 13. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 14. Nxc5 $16) (10... Ne4 11. Bc4 $1
O-O 12. O-O $36) (10... O-O 11. Nxc5 $14) 11. d4 O-O 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Bc4 $36
{Black has the c5 weakness, White has the e3 weakness, but White's pieces are
more active so we can consider this position as complicated but with higher
chances for White}) 10. exd4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O 13. Be2 Rd8 14.
Bc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Qb4 16. O-O Rxd2 17. Qe1 $11 {White will continue with Bf3
next but Black should be able to equalize with a few accurate moves}) 9. Rc1 b6
10. exd4 (10. Bb5 {leads to a complicated position, Where it is not clear at
all which side has the higher chances} Nb4 $1 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. O-O b5 13.
exd4 bxa4 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxg7 Rg8 16. Re1+ Be7 17. Be5 $1 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Kf8
19. Qf3 (19. Qh5 Rg7 $11) 19... Bf6 $11 {not easy for White to continue the
attack, but also not easy for Black to coordinate his pieces. For this reason
engine gives the 0.00 sentence}) 10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Bxd4 {here Pragg
has played the less accurate Be7} Bd6 (12... Be7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Be2 Nd5 15.
O-O {and Aronian won a nice game that you can check in the model games section}
) 13. Be2 (13. Qe2+ Be6 14. Qb5+ Bd7 $11) 13... O-O 14. O-O Bxa4 $1 15. Bxf6 (
15. bxa4 $2 Bxh2+ $15) 15... Bxb3 16. Bxd8 Bxd1 17. Rfxd1 Rfxd8 $11 {I am not
able to break my own Black side repertoire, and what I gave you in this
Chapter 13 is one possible try that has high practical value because it is
much less known compared to other more classical directions} *

