1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 3. b3 {Another possible move order to reenter into the 1.b3
repertoire.} Nf6 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. Bb5 {Using the fact that the pawn is still on
a7, and not on a6, we develop on b5 and fight directly for the long diagonal
and the central d4-e5 squares.} Bd7 6. c4 {Oparin chose to strike immediately
in the center, which is also a very good way to continue.} (6. O-O a6 7. Bxc6
Bxc6 8. Ne5 Rc8 (8... e6 9. d3 {[%cal Bb1d2,Bf2f4] It is another possible
setup, in a true Bogo-Indian style.}) 9. d3 e6 10. Nd2 {This is the way I used
to win games in my childhood, it shows how things can go terribly wrong for
Black if not careful.} Bd6 11. f4 O-O 12. Qe2 Nd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Qh5 Qc7 $4
15. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 16. Qg5+ Kh8 17. Qf6+ Kg8 18. Rf3 $18) 6... a6 {Not the only
move Black had, but very logical.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 Rc8 {Black can't allow
that we spoil the structure.} 9. O-O e6 10. Nxc6 {Now, White decided to change
the dynamic of the position.} Rxc6 11. Bxf6 $1 {A very strong idea and it
probably came as a shock to the very experienced opponent, Eljanov. We give
the monster bishop on b2, our soul of all the 1.b3 repertoire, to start
immediately putting pressure on the weak light squares in Black's position.
Very creative preparation by Oparin, who is also, by the way, Caruana's second.}
gxf6 {Objectively, a bad decision, there was no need to ruin the pawn
structure.} (11... Qxf6 {This would be the natural recapture, but probably
Eljanov was annoyed by some concrete problems.} 12. cxd5 {Hitting the rook
with tempo.} exd5 13. Nc3 {...d4 is a complete disaster, so Black has to waste
another move to defend d5.} Qf5 {Not an easy move to find, as it stops the
White queen from activating.} (13... Rd6 $2 {This is cooperative, after} 14. e4
$1 {Black is probably close to being lost, as he has to give away the d5,
otherwise} d4 $4 15. e5 $18 {[%cal Gf6e5,Gf1e1] And Black can resign.}) 14. Re1
{Even here, Black still needs to be more careful.}) 12. cxd5 {Of course, we
give no time for Black to push ...d4.} Qxd5 {Forced, ...exd5 is not really an
option.} 13. Nc3 Qd3 {Logical, to maintain the pressure on d2, and also stop
Qc2 or Qe2.} 14. Rc1 Be7 {Already a slight inaccuracy, as it commits the
bishop's position too early.} (14... h5 {Was what engine preferred, taking
control of the h5 square and also remaining flexible with the bishop (it can
go to the long diagonal sometimes too).}) 15. Ne2 {Very good regrouping, the
rook on c1 now comes to life, and also the knight is rerouted to f4 or g3 where
it has more future than on c3.} Rg8 $6 (15... O-O 16. Nf4 Qf5 17. Qf3 $14 {
More resilient for Black, but still a very long way until fighting for some
equality.}) 16. g3 $1 {First line by engine and very instructive move, Oparin
is not in a hurry at all to reveal all the ideas, he just plays a useful move
eliminating all the pressure from the g-line.} Kf8 {Black understands move too
late that his king is unsafe, now this is very ugly.} 17. Nf4 {Now it is time
to strike.} Qf5 18. d4 $1 {And Black is in serious trouble, as taking on d4 is
not that appealing, but also White is threatening d5 himself. White went on to
win a nice game, and an incredible performance by Oparin, who from a very typical
position, made Eljanov crumble in a matter of very short time.} e5 (18... cxd4
19. Rxc6 bxc6 20. Qxd4 e5 21. Qd3 {Black's structure is horrible, the endgame
is very unpleasant and I don't think someone can hold it.}) (18... Kg7 $6 19.
d5 $1 Rd6 20. Rxc5 $16) 19. Ng2 Qh3 20. Qf3 Rg6 {Black tried to organize some
threats against the king, but the strategic battle was already won by White.}
21. Rfd1 Rh6 22. Kf1 Qxh2 23. d5 $1 {Shutting down the position, and the
bishop on e7 becomes a prisoner of his own pawns.} Rb6 24. e4 $1 f5 {Some
desperate tries, after this White won basically on auto-pilot.} 25. exf5 Rb4
26. Rc4 Rxc4 27. bxc4 Qh5 {The admission of defeat basically, every endgame
with such a knight against bishop can not be holdable.} 28. Qxh5 Rxh5 29. Ke2
b5 30. d6 Bd8 31. cxb5 axb5 32. Ne3 Ke8 33. d7+ Ke7 34. Nd5+ Kf8 35. f6 e4 36.
Ne7 b4 37. Nc6 Bxf6 38. Rd6 {Incredible performance by Oparin.} 1-0

