1. c4 {The game started as an English opening, but soon we will transpose.} (1.
b3 c5 {Is another possible way to achieve the position reached in the game.})
1... c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e3 d6 6. Nge2 e5 7. b3 Nge7 8. Bb2
O-O 9. O-O {Now we transposed in our repertoire. (Chapter 2)} Rb8 {Logical
approach, Black plans an expansion on the queenside.} 10. Nd5 {White can argue
that the Nd5 jump is quite mistimed, as Levan could have at least played a
useful move, wait for ...a6 and only then play Nd5.} (10. f4 {Is the typical
way of proceeding, followed by d3-Nd5-Qd2-Nec3 and double the rooks on the
f-file with some pressure.}) 10... b5 {Black continues his plan.} (10... Nxd5
$1 {was the best way to punish the early Nd5.} 11. cxd5 (11. Bxd5 $6 {It's too
slow, now Black gets a dream scenario.} Bh3 $1 12. Bg2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 d5 $1 {
Black exchanged all of White's good pieces and managed to push d5, so the
hole on d5 is gone, which means that Black has just a slightly more pleasant
game, due to the strong center pawns.}) 11... Nb4 $1 {Using the fact that
white has to deal with ...Nd3 now.} 12. d3 a5 $132 {And the position becomes
double-edged.}) 11. d3 {We keep the tension, as we need to keep control of the
d5 square.} a6 {A strange move, hard to explain why, so probably there were
some problems with the annotation of the moves (10.d3 a6 11.Nd5 b5 is much
more logical).} 12. Qd2 f5 $6 {It's an unnecessary move, as anyway hopes for
an attack on the kingside are gone for Black, so the only thing it does is
restrain its own pieces.} (12... Bd7 {Was more in the spirit, also to keep an
eye on the c6-square, and Black plans to continue with a5-a4.}) 13. f4 $1 {
Our usual reaction to ...f5.} Be6 14. Rac1 {Maybe on e1 the rook was better
placed.} (14. Rae1 Bf7 15. Nec3 {We continue normally and hope that Black
makes a mistake, like, for example} b4 $2 {Black shouldn't release the tension
without anything in return} 16. Na4 $1 {The knight looks ugly, but it does a
great job of putting pressure on the c5 pawn, and now, we are threatening fxe5 and
d4. Black's position can become very very dubious if he is not careful.}) 14...
Rc8 (14... Bxd5 {The concrete way to play is very risky for Black.} 15. cxd5
Nb4 {Black wins a pawn, but the compensation is very good for White.} 16. e4
Nxa2 17. Ra1 Nb4 18. Kh1 {The light squares are more important than a pawn,
and it's tough to come up with something to equalize for Black.}) 15. Nec3 {
We finally mobilized all of our minor pieces, the engine says that White has a
very pleasant advantage (+0.50).} Qa5 {Some strange moves by Black, but to be
fair it's tough to come up with some kind of a concrete plan for Black.} 16.
Rfd1 {16.Rf2 can also be considered.} Rfe8 17. a3 {Useful, hinting at some b4
in the future.} Qd8 18. Nxe7+ {Now, Levan started a concrete operation.} Qxe7
19. Nd5 Qf7 $6 {Black needed to control the b6 square.} 20. Nb6 $1 {Nicely
spotted.} Rc7 21. b4 $1 {And suddenly, all of black's central pawns become
fragile, and can simply collapse.} exf4 {A big concession, and an admission of
defeat for the center, as we replace the f4 pawn with the sleepy g3 pawn,
while Black simply gets rid of the e5 pawn.} 22. gxf4 Ne7 23. bxc5 {And now
Panstulaia wanted to crush open the center.} Rxc5 (23... dxc5 {Is even worse.}
24. Bxg7 Qxg7 25. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5] And the pawn just advances.}) 24. Bxg7 Qxg7
25. d4 {And now Jakovenko went for the only practical decision left after
losing the central battle.} Rxc4 26. Nxc4 Bxc4 {Black gave up an exchange for
a pawn and knight and some weak squares, the evaluation is around +1 for White,
but later some mistakes happened in the time trouble and the game ended in a
draw.} 27. Qa5 g5 28. Qxa6 gxf4 29. exf4 Ng6 30. Qc6 Re6 31. Qf3 Nh4 32. Qa8+
Kf7 33. Rc3 Qg4 34. Rb1 Qxf4 35. Rxc4 Qe3+ 36. Kh1 Qe1+ 37. Bf1 Qxb1 38. Rc7+
Re7 39. Qd5+ Kg6 40. Qxd6+ Kh5 41. Kg1 Nf3+ 42. Kg2 Nh4+ 43. Kg1 Nf3+ 1/2-1/2

