1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Bd6 5. b3 c5 6. Bb2 {Now we transpose to
our repertoire.} Nc6 7. cxd5 {We capture before Black has the opportunity to
push d4.} exd5 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Be2 {And now we enter some kind of
Tarrasch territory, but usually Black has the bishop on e7. It has its own
pluses and minuses.} Re8 11. O-O Nxd4 (11... a6 {Is more in the spirit, and to
continue next with Bc7-Qd6, but in this game, Radoslaw went for a concrete way
to try and sterilize the game, which he didn't manage to.}) 12. Qxd4 Be5 {
The whole point is that Black can play ...d4 and get rid of the isolated pawn,
otherwise, this makes no sense.} 13. Qd2 d4 14. exd4 Qxd4 (14... Bxd4 $6 {
Is dubious, as White is much better developed, and also Black runs into some
direct problems.} 15. Rad1 $1 Bb6 16. Qg5 {And the position is very dangerous
to play from the Black side.}) 15. Qxd4 Bxd4 {The endgame seems equal at first
sight, but actually Black has one more problem to solve, the development of
the queenside.} 16. Bf3 $1 {Only move to put pressure, otherwise Black simply
develops and has no problems.} Be6 {Radoslaw decided to sacrifice the pawn
this way, and it is based on a beautiful tactical shot.} (16... Rb8 {Was the
most natural way, simply to try to defend the pawn and only then develop the
bishop.} 17. Rad1 Be5 18. h3 Bf5 {Was definitely better than what happened in
the game.}) (16... Ne4 {Was a more concrete way to solve the issues.} 17. Bxe4
Bxc3 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Bxc3 {This endgame should be pretty close to a draw,
but of course, White can press due to the extra pawn.}) 17. Rad1 $1 {Very good
move by Vitiugov, correctly assessing that 17.Bxb7 leads to nowhere, White
uses the tempo to attack the bishop, and Black is forced to take, as otherwise,
the tactics will not work anymore.} (17. Bxb7 Rab8 18. Bf3 Bxb3 $1 {Nicely
spotted from afar.} 19. axb3 Rxb3 {And Black regains the piece.}) 17... Bxc3
18. Bxc3 {The bishop pair is an incredibly strong asset in such an open
position.} Rac8 $1 {Inviting again White to take on f6 and on b7, in order to
gain activity and enter the 2nd rank with the rook, and try to defend a pawn
down endgame.} 19. Bd4 {Nikita decides to keep the bishop pair.} b6 20. Rd2 {
Prophylaxis against ...Rc2.} Bf5 21. Be3 $6 (21. Bb7 $1 {Was better, to keep
the pair alive, and also the bishop from a6 ties down black.} Rc7 22. Ba6 $14 {
White can follow with f3 to control the e4 square and double the rooks on the
d-line with a nice advantage.}) 21... Be4 $1 {Trying to change the bishop and
also aiming for ...Nd5, which was maybe missed by White.} 22. Bxe4 (22. Be2 Nd5
$1 {And black starts his own counterplay.}) 22... Rxe4 23. Rfd1 Kf8 24. h3 Re6
25. Rd4 {Even after trading the light-squared bishops, the position remains
unpleasant, as the bishop is a much better piece than the knight. The game did
not continue very long due to a terrible blunder by Wojtaszek.} h6 26. Ra4 Re7
27. Rdd4 Ke8 28. g4 {And now we just grab space and plan to bring the king.}
Rd8 29. Rxd8+ Kxd8 30. g5 $6 {It's actually not in White's interest to trade
the pawns like this, Nikita could have continued to build up pressure and only
then strike, but it worked out in the end.} Ng8 $4 {A terrible blunder,
probably it was because of a big-time scramble, otherwise it's tough to
imagine how to go for such an ugly move, but also it just loses 2 pawns by
force.} (30... hxg5 31. Bxg5 Rd7 32. Bxf6+ gxf6 {Probably both players thought
that there are good chances to win here for White, but objectively Black can
hold.}) 31. Bxb6+ $1 {Using the bad placement of Black's pieces.} axb6 32. Ra8+
Kd7 33. Rxg8 hxg5 34. Rxg7 {And Black can't defend at the same time f7 and g5
pawns. Overall, both players played a decent game, and Vitiugov showed us that
even in such endgames, seemingly drawish positions, there is play for White,
a small initiative that can turn into your opponent panicking and making
inaccuracies, and the punishment of it leading to a slight advantage for White,
with 0 risk and good chances to convert.} 1-0

