1. b3 Nf6 2. Bb2 d5 3. e3 c6 {Black plays in the Slav Defence spirit.} 4. f4 {
I wanted to play in a creative way, so I opted for a reverse Dutch system, as
White gets a very good version, because of the extra tempo and also the setup
my opponent chose is not dangerous and doesn't put any pressure.} Bf5 (4... Bg4
5. Be2 Bxe2 6. Qxe2 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gd2d3,Gb1d2,Ge1c1,Ge1g1] With natural play
ahead.}) 5. Nf3 Nbd7 {Both sides focus on finishing development for now.} 6. h3
{Hinting at some g4 and also it is quite hard to play ...h5 with black, as it
gives away the g5 square, and also ...0-0 is out of the picture.} (6. Bd3 $5 {
It's another interesting way to handle the position, as the structure arising
is very volatile.} Bxd3 (6... e6 $5 {is also interesting.}) 7. cxd3 {And
White has a lot of central control and some pressure on the diagonal (g4-g5 is
an idea).}) 6... h6 {Natural, giving some space for the bishop.} 7. Nc3 {
We developed our queenside also, meaning that I intended to play 0-0-0 at
some point.} e6 8. g4 {Grabbing space.} Bh7 9. Bg2 {After I developed all of
my minor pieces, I waited for my opponent to make a decision as I wanted to
achieve opposite side castling.} Bd6 10. d3 O-O 11. Qd2 e5 12. O-O-O d4 13.
exd4 exf4 14. g5 hxg5 15. Nxg5 Nh5 16. Nxh7 f3 17. Bxf3 Bf4 18. Nxf8 Ndf6 19.
d5 Kxf8 20. dxc6 bxc6 21. Bxc6 Rc8 22. Bb7 Rc7 23. Ba6 Nd7 24. Bc4 Nb6 25. Qxf4
Nxf4 26. Kb1 Nxc4 27. dxc4 Rd7 28. a4 Rxd1+ 29. Rxd1 Qc8 30. Nd5 Ne6 31. Ba3+
Ke8 32. Ne7 Qb7 33. Rd5 Nc7 34. Nf5 1-0

