1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Bf5 3. e3 (3. Nf3 {is the setup we recommend in the course,
aiming for a double-fianchetto.}) 3... e6 4. h3 $5 {I wanted to take out my
very well-prepared opponent out of the known territory and just enter some dark
forest. Anyway, it is a useful move.} h6 {Also useful, some prophylaxis
against future g4.} 5. Nc3 {Another tricky move I found, and my opponent
immediately made a slight imprecision.} Bh7 {Too much prophylaxis,
probably Yu was scared of some of the ghosts.} 6. d4 {Now I change the pace
and the route of my ship, I play in the center and exploit the wasted time of
Black's bishop also. The 6.d4 move also combines the ideas of a normal King's
Indian setup, where black puts the bishop on g7 and then pushes for ...e5.
Same concept here, we close the bishop for now, but it has the potential to become
very active.} Nf6 7. Bd3 {Of course, I traded the annoying h7 bishop, also
pointing out that Black lost some tempos on all of the moves.} Bxd3 8. Qxd3
Nbd7 {Black is preparing some ...c5 break.} 9. O-O-O {I am not scared of
shadows and correctly understand that the battle will take place on the
kingside, so I will put my king on b1, and it is very similar to King's Indian
just that with reverse colors and also with reverse sides of the board!} Bb4 $6
{Black is anticipating e4, but anyway, I was planning on playing more calm
developing moves before deciding where to strike so I was very happy to see
this move.} (9... a5 10. Nge2 c6 {was to be preferred, hinting at some pawn
push on the queenside maybe.}) 10. Nge2 O-O {Just like we have seen in the
previous game, the ...0-0 move is the beginning of all the troubles for Black,
a bit of a careless way to handle the opening, as anyway, I was planning to
attack this side of the board.} 11. g4 c5 {Black decides to go all-in on
the queenside, as plans like ...a5-c6-b5-a4 require too much time, and don't
really achieve anything concrete, but ...c5 opens up the c-file, the queen,
but also our bishop on b2 comes to life. So, one has to balance the two sides
of the coin before rushing with such decisions.} 12. dxc5 {I traded before
giving Black a chance to push for ...c4 even at the cost of a pawn and ...Nb6.}
Qe7 {Protects the bishop in advance.} 13. Rhg1 {I am not hiding my ideas, just
crash the king on the g-file.} Nxc5 14. Qd4 {I am not threatening to take the
bishop, but anyway, d4 is a very useful square for the queen.} Nce4 {Black was
too scared to allow g5, but completely changed the structure in the center,
meaning I will have a pawn majority on the queenside for the rest of the game.}
(14... Rac8 15. g5 $40 {We just ignore what Black is doing, as there is
nothing concrete.} (15. Qxb4 $4 {This would be a terrible blunder.} Nd3+ $1 $19
{[%cal Ge7b4,Gd3c1]})) (14... e5 15. Nxd5 $1 {Is the tactical justification.
as 15.Qxb4 was still running into 15...Nd3! winning the game.}) 15. Nxe4 dxe4 {
The pawn is also quite weak.} 16. g5 $1 {Finally, I get to open the file.} hxg5
17. Qe5 $1 {Strong move, not falling for the cheap tricks my opponent prepared
with his strange moves.} (17. Rxg5 $2 {is actually a mistake, because of} Rfd8
$1 {And after moving my queen, ...Rxd1 can only be met by Kd1.} 18. Qxf6 $4 {
Seemingly winning a piece, actually loses by force.} Qxf6 19. Bxf6 Ba3+ $1 $19
{And black will win an exchange and the game.}) 17... Rfd8 18. Rxd8+ {Now I
can safely trade the rooks, without spoiling the position of my king.} Rxd8 19.
Qxg5 Ne8 {Only way to defend g7.} 20. Qe5 $1 {Double attacking g7 and e4 pawns,
suddenly Black is in huge trouble.} f5 {Only way to protect both.} 21. Nf4 {
And now Black's pawns are collapsing one by one.} Ba3 22. Rg6 {Not even in a
hurry to collect the material.} Bxb2+ 23. Kxb2 {The position is already +3 for
the engine, and I converted my advantage into a full point.} Rd6 24. Rxe6 Rxe6 25.
Qxe6+ Qf7 26. h4 Qxe6 27. Nxe6 Nf6 28. Kc3 Ng4 29. Nd8 b6 30. Nc6 Nxf2 31. Kd4
Kf7 32. Nxa7 Ke6 33. Nc8 Ng4 34. Nxb6 Ne5 35. h5 1-0

