1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Bf5 3. e3 e6 4. h3 {Again, I used this tricky move just to get
a playable game outside of theory.} h6 5. Nc3 Nf6 {Definitely an improvement
over what Yu has played against me in 2014. There is no need to waste another
tempo on ...Bh7.} 6. d4 c5 {Black starts immediately to put pressure on my
position, and now I am not so ready to open up the diagonal, as David wasted
no time on some strange moves, and I am not in time to achieve my desired
setup.} 7. Nf3 {I change the pace and play in a more positional way.} (7. dxc5
{Would be too premature.} Bxc5 8. Qd2 $6 {Just to demonstrate how this is bad
now.} Nc6 9. O-O-O Qa5 {And Black is very active, White is under pressure on
the queenside, while no piece from my kingside is developed. This could have
ended up very badly for me.}) 7... Nc6 8. Bb5 {I aim to increase the dominance
on the dark squares, so I am happy to trade the bishop for the knight in this
type of position.} Rc8 {Logical to protect the knight.} (8... a6 {Black
shouldn't allow White to ruin his structure.} 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O Bh7 11. Na4
cxd4 12. Qxd4 {With a very solid advantage.}) 9. O-O a6 10. Bxc6+ {This was
the plan.} Rxc6 {I should say that Howell, being a very experienced
grandmaster, handled the opening very well, the position is playable and
around equal.} 11. a4 {Now my plan is to fix the dark squares on the queenside,
and at the right moment play Na4 to force Black to trade on d4.} Bh7 12. Ne5 {
I first jumped with the knight.} (12. a5 {I will show in a cooperative way,
what I was trying to achieve.} Qb8 13. Na4 Bd6 14. c3 O-O 15. Ba3 {In this
type of position, this move is nice to trade down the dark-squared bishops so
I can fully control them.} cxd4 16. exd4 Bxa3 17. Rxa3 {This would be a dream
scenario for us, fully controlling all of the dark squares, while the
bishop on h7 does very little to contribute.}) 12... Rc8 13. a5 Be7 14. Na4 {
Of course, I went for this move not in the best circumstance so to say, but
when the pawn was hanging, because I was not playing by myself, but with a very
experienced opponent who was trying to punish me in the best way possible. So, I am
not in time to prepare it for better times. But still, the idea is very good,
to take control of all of the dark squares.} cxd4 15. Qxd4 Rxc2 16. Rfc1 {
So black won a pawn, but we have good compensation on the dark squares, and
also David used a lot of time to calculate and evaluate the lines.} O-O 17. b4
{I wanted to complicate things even more.} (17. Rxc2 {Objectively the best
move in the position} Bxc2 18. Rc1 Bxb3 19. Nb6 {And the evaluation is around
equal.}) 17... Qe8 18. Rxc2 {And now some forcing line began, and the game
continued in a very sharp manner in the end I managed to win the game.} Bxc2 19.
Nc5 Qb5 20. Rc1 Bh7 21. Ncd7 $1 {This is the trick I was relying on.} Rd8 22.
Rc7 {The evaluation is still around equal, you can check the game yourself it
was also very interesting afterward.} Ne8 23. Nxf7 Rxd7 24. Nxh6+ Kf8 25. Qf4+
Nf6 26. Rc8+ Rd8 27. Rc7 Rd7 28. Rc8+ Rd8 29. Rc7 Qd3 30. Bd4 Qb1+ 31. Kh2 Qe4
32. Qg3 Nh5 33. Bxg7+ Ke8 34. Rxe7+ Kxe7 35. Qg5+ Kd7 36. Qxh5 Bg6 37. Qg5 Kc8
38. Be5 Be8 39. Bd4 Qh7 40. Ng4 Bc6 41. Qe5 Qf7 42. Ba7 Qe7 43. Bc5 Qf7 44. Nf6
Rh8 45. g4 Qg7 46. Ba7 Qc7 47. Qxc7+ Kxc7 48. Bd4 Kd6 49. Ne4+ dxe4 50. Bxh8 e5
51. Kg3 Ke6 52. h4 Ba4 53. h5 Bb5 54. Kh4 1-0

